{"title_page": "The Naked and the Dead", "text_new": "{{other uses2|The Naked and the Dead}}\n{{short description|1948 novel by Norman Mailer}}\n{{Infobox book \n| name          = The Naked and the Dead\n| author        = [[Norman Mailer]]\n| language      = English\n| country       = United States\n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[Rinehart & Company]]\n| image         = Image:TheNakedAndTheDead.jpg\n| caption       = Cover of the first edition\n| cover_artist  = \"Joe Caroff\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sergottart.com/artists/joseph-caroff/biography/ |title=Joseph Caroff Biography |work=Sergott Contemporary Art Alliance |year=2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n| illustrator   = \n| release_date  = 1948\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover) \n| pages         = 721\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''The Naked and the Dead''''' is the [[debut novel]] by [[Norman Mailer]], published in 1948 by [[Rinehart & Company]]. It depicts the wartime experiences of a platoon, based partially on Mailer's experiences as a cook<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/autodoc/page/mai0int-4 |title=Norman Mailer Interview |work=Academy of Achievement |year=2015 |location=Chicago, Illinois |accessdate=12 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323222225/http://achievement.org/autodoc/page/mai0int-4 |archivedate=23 March 2015 }}</ref> with the [[112th Cavalry Regiment]] during the [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u20131945)|Philippines Campaign]] in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Brower |first=Brock |date=24 September 1965 |title=Never the Champion, Always the Challenger |journal=LIFE |page=109 |volume=59 |issue=13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oVIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109 }}</ref> Published when he was 25 years old, the novel quickly became a bestseller, paving the way for other works such as ''[[The Deer Park]]'', ''[[Advertisements for Myself]]'', and ''[[The Time of Our Time]]''. Mailer believed ''The Naked and the Dead'' to be his most renowned work. It became the first popular novel about World War II and is considered one of the greatest English-language novels.<ref>[[John Bear]], ''The #1 New York Times Best Seller: intriguing facts about the 484 books that have been #1 New York Times bestsellers since the first list, 50 years ago'', Berkeley: Ten Speed Press, 1992, pp. 31-39</ref> It was later adapted into a [[The Naked and the Dead (film)|film]] in 1958.\n\nIn 1998 the [[Modern Library]] ranked ''The Naked and the Dead'' 51st on its list of the [[Modern Library 100 Best Novels|100 best English-language novels of the 20th century]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe novel is divided into four parts: Wave, Argil and Mold, Plant and Phantom, and Wake. Within these parts are chorus sections, consisting of play-like dialogue between characters, as well as Time Machine sections, which give brief histories and flashbacks of individual characters\u2019 lives.\n\nThe story takes place on Anopopei, a fictional island somewhere in the South Pacific. American forces are faced with a campaign to drive out the Japanese so that Americans can advance into the Philippines. The novel focuses on the experiences of one platoon.\n\n===Part One, Wave===\nCharacters are introduced as they wait around for orders. A naval bombardment takes place. The men take their places on a boat and are driven to the invasion shore. Here, they fire back and forth at the Japanese.\n\nHennessey becomes so frightened that he soils in his pants. Overcome by panic, he runs out of his foxhole and is killed by shrapnel from a mortar round. Part One concludes with this death, which alarms many of the men, since for many soldiers Hennessey\u2019s death is the first comrade death they witness.\n\n===Part Two, Argil and Mold===\nThe campaign continues. General Cummings has a soft spot for Lieutenant Hearn, the only officer he can relate to intellectually; they have many discussions together. At one point, the platoon takes a Japanese soldier as prisoner. When Gallagher gives the Japanese soldier a cigarette to smoke, the soldier closes his eyes in relaxation. At this moment, Croft shoots and kills him, demonstrating his coldblooded personality.\n\nLater, Gallagher receives word that his wife, Mary, died in childbirth. Although Gallagher\u2019s child survived, he is overcome by immense grief throughout the rest of the novel.\n\n===Part Three, Plant and Phantom===\nHearn is assigned by Cummings to lead the platoon through the jungle and up Mountain Anaka, to find a way to the rear of the enemy. After a clash with the Japanese, Wilson is shot and left behind.\n\nCroft sends men back to get Wilson. Brown, Stanley, Goldstein, and Ridges then carry Wilson back to the beach on a stretcher. The trip takes several days, and Wilson ends up dying. The men eventually lose Wilson\u2019s body in a river.\n\nCroft manipulates Hearn into walking into an ambush, and Hearn is killed, leaving Croft in charge. The men continue hiking up the mountain on Croft\u2019s orders, even though many men view it as a hopeless cause. Later, Roth dies while attempting to make a jump on the mountain\u2019s edge.\n\nTrudging on, the men eventually give up their task of climbing the mountain. They return to the beach where Brown, Stanley, Goldstein, and Ridges have arrived from their mission with Wilson.\n\nThey learn that the battle for the island is almost won. Surprisingly, the ruthless Croft seems to be relieved that he was unable to climb the mountain. At the end of Part Three, the remaining men discuss their future and how it will feel when they return home now that their mission is over.\n\n===Part Four, Wake===\nThis part consists of one short chapter. Cummings reflects on the war. He is disappointed that the victory was too easy (it came as a result of exhaustion of Japanese troops) and that he cannot take the credit, as Major Dalleson, who acted as his deputy for a day, won the battle just by obeying established procedures. Major Dalleson then wonders about the new training program that will take place with new troops the next day.\n\n==Main characters==\n\n*'''Hennessey''' is a newer member of the platoon. He is very cautious with all of his gear and movements so as to not get killed. When they arrive at the beach of Anopopei, he defecates in his pants out of fear during the opening action scene. He has a mental break down and runs down the beach in hopes of getting new pants. He is killed soon after by shrapnel from an exploding mortar shell.\n*'''Woodrow Wilson''' is a large, impoverished white Southerner. He has a happy-go-lucky and generous nature. In his \"Time Machine\" we learn Wilson wakes up married to a woman named Alice after a drunken night at the bar. Their marriage consists of love affairs and money troubles. Later, Wilson suffers a long, agonizing death after being shot in the stomach by the Japanese; Brown, Goldstein, Ridges, and Stanley try to carry him back to the beach to be saved but he dies on the way there.\n*'''Julio Martinez''' is a Mexican-American from Texas. He is nicknamed Japbait by Croft and made sergeant in General Cummings infantry division. Martinez was terrified, constantly on edge and an introvert throughout the beginning of the novel. He however, gains bravery through battle and is an excellent soldier, especially in terms of getting a scope for the land. He is well trusted by the other men in the platoon. Croft convinces Martinez to lie about a Japanese platoon he saw on a solo scouting mission, which leads to the death of Hearn and to the men hiking to Mount Anaka under Croft's command.\n*'''Sam Croft''' has a large ego and is coldblooded throughout the novel. At one point, he immorally kills a Japanese POW. Later, he squeezes Roth\u2019s baby bird to death as if he is crushing all innocence. He loves war and is Mailer\u2019s version of a psychopath within the novel. He is seen as one of the best soldiers in the platoon and the other men both fear and respect him as a leader. In his time capsule, we learned he was cheated on by the women he loved which led to him being cold and developing a love for war. At the conclusion of the book, Croft refuses to look forward to his homecoming, believing that the war will continue for much longer. After all, he enjoys the war because he finds a thrill in killing.\n*'''Red Valsen''' claims he does not want to rise in the ranks. He appears numb to death and the war itself. As a child, he grew up in a mine town in Montana. Later, he runs away from home, losing contact with his entire family. After holding many jobs, Red moves in with his girlfriend Lois and her son. Afraid of commitment, Red joins the Army and runs away from Lois. While in the Army, Red loses contact with Lois just like he did with his own family.\n*'''Lieutenant Robert Hearn''' is the stereotypical white liberal. Harvard educated and from an affluent family, Hearn is General Cummings\u2019 assistant. He despises the caste system within the Army, wishing that he could reach out to the lower class foot soldiers. Later, Cummings transfers Hearn to Dalleson\u2019s section. He leads the platoon through the jungle and to the mountain pass. Here, he is shot and killed quickly and anticlimactically not expecting Japanese resistance after Croft keeps the information from him.\n*'''General Edward Cummings''' is power-hungry, often comparing himself to God. As a child, Cummings experiences gender-role confusion. This forces his father to send him to military school. Later, Cummings attends West Point. While at West Point, he meets Margaret and feels socially pressured into marrying her. Margaret and Cummings are married and never have children. They have an unhappy marriage, perhaps due to Cummings homosexual tendencies and feelings. It is apparent through his conversations with Hearn that he has romantic feelings for him.\n*'''Roy Gallagher''' is Boston Irish and part of an Anti-Semitic gang called Christians United. He always seems angry throughout the novel. Later, he learns that his wife Mary died in childbirth, but their baby lived. Gallagher remains devastated for the rest of the novel.\n*'''Roth''' is a depressing, fickle stereotypical representation of a Jew. He, however, refuses to consider himself and strongly associate with being Jewish. Throughout the novel, he has a superiority complex because he is better educated than the other men of the platoon. Roth dies while climbing the mountain because he misses a jump and fails to grasp Gallagher\u2019s hand.\n*'''Joey Goldstein''' is also Jewish like Roth. However, unlike Roth, he does not view himself as better than his Christian friends. Goldstein grows up as a mamma\u2019s boy and desires to own his own shop. Later, he becomes a welder and marries Natalie, despite his mother\u2019s disapproval. After their son is born, Goldstein struggles to support his family and maintain a loving relationship with his wife. Throughout the war, Goldstein is well-respected by his comrades, although he does lack courage at times.\n*'''William Brown''' is the stereotypical well-liked, neighborhood boy. Growing up in a middle-class family, Brown later attends a state university. Here he joins a fraternity and flunks out by freshman year. He marries a girl from his high school, Beverly, and lives a fairly boring life. Throughout the war, he worries that Beverly will cheat on him while he\u2019s away. He is certain that he will throw her out of the house when he returns home.\n*'''Stanley''' insists that women are no different from men. He trusts his wife Ruthie, who is the mother of his child. In some ways, he is the quiet feminist within the novel. He is also more ambitious than the other soldiers, since he is inexperienced in war; he desires to move up in ranks and befriends Brown in order to do so. \n*'''Toglio''' is an Italian-American. Patriotic, trusting, and good-natured, he is friends with most of his platoon. He sustains a [[million-dollar wound]] during combat and is sent home. Subsequently, as time passes, some characters come to envy his wound and grow to hate him.\n*'''Casimir \"Polack\" Czienwicz''' comes from a lower-class Polish family. He grows up with seven siblings and, after his father dies, he enters the orphanage. At thirteen, an older woman seduces him multiple times. These experiences make Polack a tough, courageous soldier in the Army.\n*'''Oscar Ridges''' is extremely Christian. He assures Wyman, who refers to him as \u201cthe preacher,\u201d  that \u201cThe Lord\u2019ll keep me from shooting a Christian\u201d.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|218}} Despite his Christian beliefs, Ridges befriends Goldstein as his buddy. This friendship between a Jew and Christian demonstrates how the war brought men of different backgrounds together.\n*'''Buddy Wyman''' does not play a major role within the novel.  He dreams of becoming a war hero in order to support his mother and himself.\n*'''Steven Minetta''' is twenty years old and was known as the \u201cbest dresser on the block\u201d when he was growing up.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|60}} He is eventually wounded but then returns to the platoon. At the conclusion of the novel, Minetta feels anger towards power figures and hopes to \u201cexpose the goddam Army.\u201d {{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|711}}\n*'''Dalleson''' was second in command to Cummings. He was very nervous throughout the novel and did not trust his own judgment. At the end of the novel, however, it is Dalleson who helps them win the war against the Japanese Army.\n\n==Themes==\n{{original research|section|date=August 2015}}\nThroughout the novel, Mailer dwells on many themes. These themes are recurring throughout his works and reappear in several of his later essays and novels.\n\n'''Dehumanization of soldiers''' Commenting on the dehumanization of soldiers in ''The Naked and the Dead,'' Mailer said, \"The book finds man corrupted, confused to the point of helplessness, but it also find that there are limits beyond which he cannot be pushed.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lennon |first1=Michael |title=Norman Mailer: A Double Life |date=2014 |publisher=Simon & Shuster |location=New York |page=97}}</ref> The soldiers are continuously referred to as machines within the novel. At one point, the narrator describes this dehumanization stating, \u201cWhen a man was harnessed into a pack and web belt and carried a rifle and two bandoliers and several grenades, a bayonet and a helmet, he felt as if he had a tourniquet over both shoulders and across his chest. It was hard to breathe and his limbs kept falling asleep.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|24}} Thus, in this instance, the soldier is losing grasp of his bodily functions and simply going through the motions of being a \u201csoldier\u201d. \nDehumanization of the soldier is also seen in chapter 5 when the platoon had to carry antitank guns between 1st Battalion and A Company, which was about a mile of muddy trail. The men became numb and only went through the motions of carrying the guns. The generals disregarded the soldiers' exhaustion. This treatment of men as machines is reinforced throughout the novel. The expectation for the soldiers to fight off Japanese attacks despite their fear also demonstrates this dehumanization. The soldiers generally believed the army didn't see them as people and that \"they don't care if you live or die here [the infirmary]. All they want is to get you back where you can stop a bullet\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|chapter=The Naked and the Dead and Its Aftermath|pages=14\u201333|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|doi=10.2307/j.ctv6sj74q.5|isbn=978-1-61117-806-7|title=Understanding Norman Mailer|year=2017}}</ref>{{rp|354}} Meaning, when soldiers were injured, the Army didn't care about their well-being annd only cared that they would heal enough to go back out into warfare.\n\n'''Brotherhood:''' Another theme, brotherhood, is a positive feature in the novel. In feeling that they may not make it out alive, the soldiers developed strong friendships which are not relatable to people at home. Croft expresses his feelings of brotherhood and tells his comrades, \u201cYou\u2019re all good guys. You\u2019re all chicken, and you\u2019re all yellow, but you\u2019re good guys. They ain\u2019t a goddam thing wrong with you.\u201d, which is important to note considering Croft was the coldhearted character in the novel.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|202}} This idea of brotherhood is also seen within Part III when Brown, Goldstein, Ridges, and Stanley attempt to carry the wounded Wilson back to camp. Despite the physical strains of carrying Wilson back, the men presisted wanting to save Wilson. This brotherhood of the platoon is also illustrated in their reaction to the death of Hearn in comparison to the death of Roth. When Hearn, who was new to the platoon as the commander, was killed by Japanese soldiers, the platoon stood shocked for a couple of seconds and then tried to escape the fire of the Japanese. When Roth died however, \"the platoon was shattered. For ten minuted they huddled together on the shelf, too stricken, too terrified, to move on.<ref name=\":0\" />\"{{rp|684}} Roth had been with the platoon since the beginning and his death greatly effected all of the men, demonstrating the brotherhood they had with Roth and with each other.\n\n'''Loneliness:''' The theme of loneliness also reoccurs within the novel. Away from their family and friends at home, the soldiers are constantly lonely. The men in their ranks are of different social classes and religions, which sometimes makes it difficult for the men to find commonalities between one another. When they do share something in common, they see it as a unifying factor between them. For instance, Goldstein feels a connection and a sort of alliance with Roth since they are both Jewish. Although the men in the platoon do have a sense of brotherhood with one another, as mentioned above, they still feel alone during their deployment. Throughout the novel, the men also long for women and deeper friendships. Roth, for example, wishes to have someone whom he \u201ccould talk to seriously.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|51}} He realizes that he doesn\u2019t know his own comrades very well, since everyone he met when he initially entered the Army was either killed or reassigned somewhere else. The men also constantly degrade women, however, it is evident the absence of women caused them to feel lonelier and wish they were with them.\n\n'''Death and fear:''' Death and the fear of dying is another theme prevalent in the novel. The men are faced with unexpected deaths, such as Hennessey's, Wilson, Hearn, Roth, and Gallagher\u2019s wife who dies during childbirth. It is clear death surrounds them and their lives could be taken away in any moment. Cummings, having been surrounded by Army deaths the majority of his career, still never warms to the smell of rotting corpses. Red, like the other soldiers, realizes he or one of his comrades could be killed any minute. Even when they grew used to death and saw it as \"large and devastating and meaningless. Men who were killed were nearly men no longer around\", a comrade's death would cause \"the idea of death [to be] fresh and terrifying again\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|123}} This fear of death also had a negative impact on the mental health and sanity of the men. For instance, Red states, \"Goddam Army gets you so you're afraid to turn around\".{{rp|12}} The men began to have a pessimistic view of life believing \"All dead things... everything lives to die\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|228}} This was especially so since \"that's all [soldiers] can ever do in the Army, sit and think\" which caused the thoughts and fears of death to be constant and prevalent.<ref name=\":0\" /> {{rp|474}}\n\n'''Power:''' The theme of power is also in the novel through the power relations the men have with one another, especially those of high ranking with those below them. For instance, the theme is exemplified through General Cummings himself. Cummings compares himself to the \u201cchief monk\u201d and God throughout the book. He also openly supports the class system within the military, and states Hearn must accept the \u201cemotional prejudices of his class\u201d, especially since he is an officer. People of higher ranks like Hearn and Cummings, after all, enjoy a better quality of life than the other foot soldiers. They sleep in larger staterooms while the soldiers share small rooms and are jammed into cots. This power system and power relations is reinforced within the missions. After Hearn dies, Croft is \"relieved\" that there is no longer a rival to his power and takes over leading the platoon up the mountain.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|603}} While the other soldiers clearly want to stop and give up, they continue hiking the mountain simply because Croft commands them to. Chickenshit, as termed by [[Paul Fussell]] in \"Wartime: Understanding and Behavior in the Second World War\", was a major aspect of the theme of power in the novel.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=June 1991|title=Paul Fussell. <italic>Wartime: Understanding and Behavior in the Second World War</italic>. New York: Oxford University Press. 1989. Pp. x, 330. $19.95|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/96.3.843-a|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> This is shown in how Cummings makes Hearn do humiliating tasks and in the end sends him on a mission knowing he will die, which is the ultimate chickenshit since he sent him to die solely to demonstrate his power. This is another instance where the undemocratic nature of the Army is apparent.\n\n'''Homosexuality:''' The theme of homosexuality is most evident with Cummings. In his \"Time Machine\", Mailer illustrates Cummings growing up experiencing gender-role confusion. Although his mother supports Cummings' identity, his father refuses to have a son who is homosexual and thus sends him to military school. This portages the notion of the Army being only for \"real men\". However, there were a lot of homosexual men who were soldiers during WWII and as [[Allan B\u00e9rub\u00e9]] illustrates in ''Coming Out Under Fire: History of Gay Men and Women in World War Two'', they were often seen as trusted and respected soldiers and medics.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=June 1991|title=Allan Berube. <italic>Coming Out under Fire: The History of Gay Men and Women in World War Two</italic>. New York: Free Press. 1990. Pp. xiii, 377. $22.95|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/96.3.845|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> While in the Army, it is clear Cummings developed romantic feelings towards Hearn and sexually desired him. Through Cummings, Mailer illustrates his beliefs of homosexuality. Although Mailer believes being homosexual is evil, it is interesting he had the general be the homosexual character in the novel, especially since he depicts the general as being a powerful figure who is a good leader. Mailer also includes homosexual characters in his other works as well, such as in ''[[The Deer Park]].'' Mailer directly addresses this theme and his beliefs of homosexuality in \"The Homosexual Villain\" stating he saw homosexuals as evil and always depicted them as the villain in his works but realized they were humans.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mailer, Norman.|title=The homosexual villain|oclc=21704456}}</ref>\n\n'''Misogyny:''' The theme of misogyny also occurs within the novel. Like Mailer\u2019s other works, ''The Naked and the Dead'' constantly portrays women as sexual objects who are below men. Many men, especially Brown, fear their wives are cheating on them while they are at war. This only causes them to have more hatred towards women and a deep distrust towards them. Brown tells Stanley that if he finds out his wife cheated on him, he will beat her then throw her out.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|168}} Later, in the Chorus \u201cWomen,\u201d Polack insists that \u201cthere ain\u2019t a fuggin woman is any good\u201d and Brown agrees. Women are especially emphasized within \"Time Machine\" segments. In these segments, the men\u2019s romantic relationships and sexual experiences are described in detail. In many of the \"Time Machines\", such as Martinez's, women are portrayed as simply sexual objects. In Croft's \"Time Machine\", we learn was cheated on by the women he loved which resulted in him being cold and having a hatred towards women. The men seem to disregard the fact that they have cheated several times on their partners but show extreme hatred in the thought of their wives cheating on them. The only character that seems to positively view his wife is Gallagher, who becomes miserable and lost after she dies. This deep hatred for women, however, is a way to mask how strongly these men miss and desire women; they desperately need women for a variety of different reasons.\n\n==Development==\n'''Writing development:''' Before he left for basic training, Mailer was certain that he could write \u201cTHE war novel\u201d based on his experiences as a cook and the experiences of soldiers in World War II.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Christopher |last=Beha |title=Does Mailer Matter? The Young Writer and the last literary celebrity |journal=Harper's Magazine |issue=88}}</ref>  After returning home from the war, he moved to France with his first wife, Beatrice, where he studied at the Sorbonne in [[Paris]].  Here, in just 15 months, Mailer wrote his war novel as noted in his introduction to its Fiftieth Anniversary Edition.<ref name=\"martinfrost.ws\">{{cite web|url=http://www.martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/jan2009/norman-mailer.html |title=Frost's Meditations |website=martinfrost.ws |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923062046/http://www.martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/jan2009/norman-mailer.html |archivedate=September 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nMailer states his writing inspiration came from the great Russian novelists like [[Leo Tolstoy]]. While writing, Mailer often read \u201cfrom [[Anna Karenina]] most mornings before he commenced his own work.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|7}} Mailer believed Tolstoy enabled him to bring compassion to his pages; Tolstoy taught him that \u201ccompassion is valueless without severity.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|8}} Mailer was convinced he brought this compassion to ''The Naked and the Dead'', and it is what enabled a 25-year-old to write an incredible war novel.\n\nThroughout his writing process, Mailer explained, he \u201cused to write twenty-five pages of first draft a week,\u201d which allowed his novel to flow from page to page.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.odysseyeditions.com/EBooks/Norman-Mailer/The-Naked-and-the-Dead/Author-commentary |title=The Naked and the Dead: Author commentary |first=Norman |last=Mailer |work=odysseyeditions.com |year=2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Mailer felt this novel was the easiest for him to write, as he finished it quickly and passionately. He later stated, \u201cPart of me thought it was possibly the greatest book written since [[War and Peace]].\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xi}}\n\nDespite the author\u2019s self-praise, he acknowledged his writing immaturity within the novel. Mailer insisted \u201cit was sloppily written in many parts (the words came too quickly and too easily) and there was hardly a noun in any sentence that was not holding hands with the nearest and most commonly available adjective.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xi}} However, despite this criticism, Mailer believed the book deserved to be a best seller. It was written with vigor and contained acute descriptiveness which enabled readers to imagine what World War II was really like. Mailer admitted that he still returned to ''The Naked and the Dead'' occasionally and reread passages because they gave him hope \u201cfor all of us.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xiii}}\n\n'''Character that represents Mailer:''' Mailer stated he did not portray himself as one of the characters. However, he mentions the character of Roth is the most similar to himself. He states Roth's experiences within the novel closely resembled his own experiences in WWII, especially in comparison to the other characters. This similarity is also evident in how they are both Jewish but don't necessarily strongly declare being Jewish.\n\n=== \"Fug\" ===\nThe publishers of ''The Naked and the Dead'' prevented Mailer from using the word \"fuck\" in his novel and had to use the [[euphemism]] \"fug\" instead. Mailer's version of a subsequent incident follows:\n               \n<blockquote>The word has been a source of great embarrassment to me over the years because, you know, Tallulah Bankhead's press agent, many years ago, got a story in the papers which went...\"Oh, hello, you're Norman Mailer,\" said Tallulah Bankhead allegedly, \"You're the young man that doesn't know how to spell...\" You know, the four-letter word was indicated with all sorts of asterisks.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lennon |first=Michael |last2=Mailer |first2=Norman |editor-last=Lennon |editor-first=J. Michael |year=1988 |chapter=1968 Panel Discussion, CBLT-TV, Toronto, moderated by Robert Fulford |title=Conversations with Norman Mailer |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=978-0878053513 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe incident is mentioned in [[John Green (author)|John Green]]'s ''[[An Abundance of Katherines]]''. Colin Singleton tells Lindsey Lee Wells he likes to read literary criticism after reading a book. Colin says the publisher indicated that no one in 1948 would buy ''The Naked and the Dead''  \"'because it contains even more F-bombs than it does Regular Bombs.' So Norman Mailer, as a kind of fug-you to the publisher, went through his 872-page book and changed every last F-word to 'fug.'\"  <ref>{{Citation |last=Green |first=John |pages=[https://archive.org/details/abundanceofkathe00gree/page/119 119\u2013120] |title=An Abundance of Katherines |year=2006 |publisher=Penguin Group |isbn=978-0-525-47688-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/abundanceofkathe00gree/page/119 }}</ref>\n\nThe rock band [[the Fugs]] took their name from this word.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefugs.com/history2.html|title=History of The Fugs|last1=Sanders|first1=Ed|website=The Fugs|publisher=Metze Publication Design|quote=[Tuli Kupferberg] was the one who came up with the name, the Fugs, borrowed from the euphemism in Normal [sic] Mailer's novel, The Naked and the Dead.}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Wikiquote|Norman Mailer#The Naked and the Dead|The Naked and the Dead}}\nIn 1948, at the age of twenty-five, Mailer published ''The Naked and the Dead,'' which was extremely successful. The book sold 200,000 copies in its first three months and remained on the ''New York Times'' best seller list for 62 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Lehmann-Hauptm |title=Norman Mailer, Towering Author with Matching Ego, Dies at 84 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=10 November 2007 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/10/books/11mailer.html?pagewanted=2&_r=1&hp&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1386183694-I%20VYF5Ha7SZvP1EE5Mp6KA& |url-access=subscription }}</ref>  Later, Modern Library named ''The Naked and the Dead'' one of the top hundred novels in the English language.<ref name=\"martinfrost.ws\"/>\n\nPublisher [[Bennett Cerf]] declared in 1948 \"only three novels published since the first of the year that were worth reading ... ''[[Cry, the Beloved Country]]'', ''[[The Ides of March (novel)|The Ides of March]]'', and ''The Naked and the Dead''.\"<ref name=\"rd\">{{cite news |title=Reader's digest: Gossip, news: J. F. Albright reports on A.B.A. meeting |title-link=American Booksellers Association |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |date=30 May 1948 |page=6 }}</ref>\n\nIn its initial review the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' complained that the novel \"grows increasingly unreadable\" due to Mailer's tendency to \"leave nothing out\".<ref>Ross, Alan. \"Under Fire.\" The Times Literary Supplement, 20 May 1949, p. 325.</ref> The ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' described the novel as \"dull\" for the same reason.<ref>Johnson, Pamela Hansford. \"New Fiction.\" Daily Telegraph, 13 May 1949, p. 6.</ref>\n\nLater, [[Gore Vidal]] would write:\n\n<blockquote>My first reaction to ''The Naked and the Dead'' was: it\u2019s a fake. A clever, talented, admirably executed fake. I have not changed my opinion of the book since\u2026 I do recall a fine description of men carrying a dying man down a mountain\u2026 Yet every time I got going in the narrative I would find myself stopped cold by a set of made-up, predictable characters taken not from life, but from the same novels all of us had read, and informed by a na\u00efvet\u00e9 which was at its worst when Mailer went into his Time-Machine and wrote those passages which resemble nothing so much as smudged carbons of a [[John Dos Passos|Dos Passos]] work.<ref>{{Citation |last=Vidal |first=Gore |authorlink=Gore Vidal |origyear=1960 |year=1993 |title=United States: Essays 1952\u20131992 |chapter=Norman Mailer\u2019s Self-Advertisements |publisher=Random House |location=New York |page=[https://archive.org/details/unitedstates00gore/page/32 32] |isbn=978-0-679-75572-2 |title-link=United States: Essays 1952\u20131992 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n;Bibliography\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Mailer |first=Norman |title=The Naked and the Dead |location=New York |publisher=Henry Holt & Company |year=1948 |edition=50th Anniversary }}\n\n{{Norman Mailer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naked and the Dead}}\n[[Category:1948 American novels]]\n[[Category:Rinehart & Company books]]\n[[Category:World War II novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Novels by Norman Mailer]]\n[[Category:Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Novels set on islands]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:1948 debut novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|The Naked and the Dead}}\n{{short description|1948 novel by Norman Mailer}}\n{{Infobox book \n| name          = The Naked and the Dead\n| author        = [[Norman Mailer]]\n| language      = English\n| country       = United States\n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[Rinehart & Company]]\n| image         = Image:TheNakedAndTheDead.jpg\n| caption       = Cover of the first edition\n| cover_artist  = \"Joe Caroff\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sergottart.com/artists/joseph-caroff/biography/ |title=Joseph Caroff Biography |work=Sergott Contemporary Art Alliance |year=2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n| illustrator   = \n| release_date  = 1948\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover) \n| pages         = 721\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''The Naked and the Dead''''' is the [[debut novel]] by [[Norman Mailer]], published in 1948 by [[Rinehart & Company]]. It depicts the wartime experiences of a platoon, based partially on Mailer's experiences as a cook<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/autodoc/page/mai0int-4 |title=Norman Mailer Interview |work=Academy of Achievement |year=2015 |location=Chicago, Illinois |accessdate=12 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323222225/http://achievement.org/autodoc/page/mai0int-4 |archivedate=23 March 2015 }}</ref> with the [[112th Cavalry Regiment]] during the [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u20131945)|Philippines Campaign]] in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Brower |first=Brock |date=24 September 1965 |title=Never the Champion, Always the Challenger |journal=LIFE |page=109 |volume=59 |issue=13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oVIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109 }}</ref> Published when he was 25 years old, the novel quickly became a bestseller, paving the way for other works such as ''[[The Deer Park]]'', ''[[Advertisements for Myself]]'', and ''[[The Time of Our Time]]''. Mailer believed ''The Naked and the Dead'' to be his most renowned work. It became the first popular novel about World War II and is considered one of the greatest English-language novels.<ref>[[John Bear]], ''The #1 New York Times Best Seller: intriguing facts about the 484 books that have been #1 New York Times bestsellers since the first list, 50 years ago'', Berkeley: Ten Speed Press, 1992, pp. 31-39</ref> It was later adapted into a [[The Naked and the Dead (film)|film]] in 1958.\n\nIn 1998 the [[Modern Library]] ranked ''The Naked and the Dead'' 51st on its list of the [[Modern Library 100 Best Novels|100 best English-language novels of the 20th century]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe novel is divided into four parts: Wave, Argil and Mold, Plant and Phantom, and Wake. Within these parts are chorus sections, consisting of play-like dialogue between characters, as well as Time Machine sections, which give brief histories and flashbacks of individual characters\u2019 lives.\n\nThe story takes place on Anopopei, a fictional island somewhere in the South Pacific. American forces are faced with a campaign to drive out the Japanese so that Americans can advance into the Philippines. The novel focuses on the experiences of one platoon.\n\n===Part One, Wave===\nCharacters are introduced as they wait around for orders. A naval bombardment takes place. The men take their places on a boat and are driven to the invasion shore. Here, they fire back and forth at the Japanese.\n\nHennessey becomes so frightened that he soils in his pants. Overcome by panic, he runs out of his foxhole and is killed by shrapnel from a mortar round. Part One concludes with this death, which alarms many of the men, since for many soldiers Hennessey\u2019s death is the first comrade death they witness.\n\n===Part Two, Argil and Mold===\nThe campaign continues. General Cummings has a soft spot for Lieutenant Hearn, the only officer he can relate to intellectually; they have many discussions together. At one point, the platoon takes a Japanese soldier as prisoner. When Gallagher gives the Japanese soldier a cigarette to smoke, the soldier closes his eyes in relaxation. At this moment, Croft shoots and kills him, demonstrating his coldblooded personality.\n\nLater, Gallagher receives word that his wife, Mary, died in childbirth. Although Gallagher\u2019s child survived, he is overcome by immense grief throughout the rest of the novel.\n\n===Part Three, Plant and Phantom===\nHearn is assigned by Cummings to lead the platoon through the jungle and up Mountain Anaka, to find a way to the rear of the enemy. After a clash with the Japanese, Wilson is shot and left behind.\n\nCroft sends men back to get Wilson. Brown, Stanley, Goldstein, and Ridges then carry Wilson back to the beach on a stretcher. The trip takes several days, and Wilson ends up dying. The men eventually lose Wilson\u2019s body in a river.\n\nCroft manipulates Hearn into walking into an ambush, and Hearn is killed, leaving Croft in charge. The men continue hiking up the mountain on Croft\u2019s orders, even though many men view it as a hopeless cause. Later, Roth dies while attempting to make a jump on the mountain\u2019s edge.\n\nTrudging on, the men eventually give up their task of climbing the mountain. They return to the beach where Brown, Stanley, Goldstein, and Ridges have arrived from their mission with Wilson.\n\nThey learn that the battle for the island is almost won. Surprisingly, the ruthless Croft seems to be relieved that he was unable to climb the mountain. At the end of Part Three, the remaining men discuss their future and how it will feel when they return home now that their mission is over.\n\n===Part Four, Wake===\nThis part consists of one short chapter. Cummings reflects on the war. He is disappointed that the victory was too easy (it came as a result of exhaustion of Japanese troops) and that he cannot take the credit, as Major Dalleson, who acted as his deputy for a day, won the battle just by obeying established procedures. Major Dalleson then wonders about the new training program that will take place with new troops the next day.\n\n==Main characters==\n\n*'''Hennessey''' is a newer member of the platoon. He is very cautious with all of his gear and movements so as to not get killed. When they arrive at the beach of Anopopei, he defecates in his pants out of fear during the opening action scene. He has a mental break down and runs down the beach in hopes of getting new pants. He is killed soon after by shrapnel from an exploding mortar shell.\n*'''Woodrow Wilson''' is a large, impoverished white Southerner. He has a happy-go-lucky and generous nature. In his \"Time Machine\" we learn Wilson wakes up married to a woman named Alice after a drunken night at the bar. Their marriage consists of love affairs and money troubles. Later, Wilson suffers a long, agonizing death after being shot in the stomach by the Japanese; Brown, Goldstein, Ridges, and Stanley try to carry him back to the beach to be saved but he dies on the way there.\n*'''Julio Martinez''' is a Mexican-American from Texas. He is nicknamed Japbait by Croft and made sergeant in General Cummings infantry division. Martinez was terrified, constantly on edge and an introvert throughout the beginning of the novel. He however, gains bravery through battle and is an excellent soldier, especially in terms of getting a scope for the land. He is well trusted by the other men in the platoon. Croft convinces Martinez to lie about a Japanese platoon he saw on a solo scouting mission, which leads to the death of Hearn and to the men hiking to Mount Anaka under Croft's command.\n*'''Sam Croft''' has a large ego and is coldblooded throughout the novel. At one point, he immorally kills a Japanese POW. Later, he squeezes Roth\u2019s baby bird to death as if he is crushing all innocence. He loves war and is Mailer\u2019s version of a psychopath within the novel. He is seen as one of the best soldiers in the platoon and the other men both fear and respect him as a leader. In his time capsule, we learned he was cheated on by the women he loved which led to him being cold and developing a love for war. At the conclusion of the book, Croft refuses to look forward to his homecoming, believing that the war will continue for much longer. After all, he enjoys the war because he finds a thrill in killing.\n*'''Red Valsen''' claims he does not want to rise in the ranks. He appears numb to death and the war itself. As a child, he grew up in a mine town in Montana. Later, he runs away from home, losing contact with his entire family. After holding many jobs, Red moves in with his girlfriend Lois and her son. Afraid of commitment, Red joins the Army and runs away from Lois. While in the Army, Red loses contact with Lois just like he did with his own family.\n*'''Lieutenant Robert Hearn''' is the stereotypical white liberal. Harvard educated and from an affluent family, Hearn is General Cummings\u2019 assistant. He despises the caste system within the Army, wishing that he could reach out to the lower class foot soldiers. Later, Cummings transfers Hearn to Dalleson\u2019s section. He leads the platoon through the jungle and to the mountain pass. Here, he is shot and killed quickly and anticlimactically not expecting Japanese resistance after Croft keeps the information from him.\n*'''General Edward Cummings''' is power-hungry, often comparing himself to God. As a child, Cummings experiences gender-role confusion. This forces his father to send him to military school. Later, Cummings attends West Point. While at West Point, he meets Margaret and feels socially pressured into marrying her. Margaret and Cummings are married and never have children. They have an unhappy marriage, perhaps due to Cummings homosexual tendencies and feelings. It is apparent through his conversations with Hearn that he has romantic feelings for him.\n*'''Roy Gallagher''' is Boston Irish and part of an Anti-Semitic gang called Christians United. He always seems angry throughout the novel. Later, he learns that his wife Mary died in childbirth, but their baby lived. Gallagher remains devastated for the rest of the novel.\n*'''Roth''' is a depressing, fickle stereotypical representation of a Jew. He, however, refuses to consider himself and strongly associate with being Jewish. Throughout the novel, he has a superiority complex because he is better educated than the other men of the platoon. Roth dies while climbing the mountain because he misses a jump and fails to grasp Gallagher\u2019s hand.\n*'''Joey Goldstein''' is also Jewish like Roth. However, unlike Roth, he does not view himself as better than his Christian friends. Goldstein grows up as a mamma\u2019s boy and desires to own his own shop. Later, he becomes a welder and marries Natalie, despite his mother\u2019s disapproval. After their son is born, Goldstein struggles to support his family and maintain a loving relationship with his wife. Throughout the war, Goldstein is well-respected by his comrades, although he does lack courage at times.\n*'''William Brown''' is the stereotypical well-liked, neighborhood boy. Growing up in a middle-class family, Brown later attends a state university. Here he joins a fraternity and flunks out by freshman year. He marries a girl from his high school, Beverly, and lives a fairly boring life. Throughout the war, he worries that Beverly will cheat on him while he\u2019s away. He is certain that he will throw her out of the house when he returns home.\n*'''Stanley''' insists that women are no different from men. He trusts his wife Ruthie, who is the mother of his child. In some ways, he is the quiet feminist within the novel. He is also more ambitious than the other soldiers, since he is inexperienced in war; he desires to move up in ranks and befriends Brown in order to do so. \n*'''Toglio''' is an Italian-American. Patriotic, trusting, and good-natured, he is friends with most of his platoon. He sustains a [[million-dollar wound]] during combat and is sent home. Subsequently, as time passes, some characters come to envy his wound and grow to hate him.\n*'''Casimir \"Polack\" Czienwicz''' comes from a lower-class Polish family. He grows up with seven siblings and, after his father dies, he enters the orphanage. At thirteen, an older woman seduces him multiple times. These experiences make Polack a tough, courageous soldier in the Army.\n*'''Oscar Ridges''' is extremely Christian. He assures Wyman, who refers to him as \u201cthe preacher,\u201d  that \u201cThe Lord\u2019ll keep me from shooting a Christian\u201d.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|218}} Despite his Christian beliefs, Ridges befriends Goldstein as his buddy. This friendship between a Jew and Christian demonstrates how the war brought men of different backgrounds together.\n*'''Buddy Wyman''' does not play a major role within the novel.  He dreams of becoming a war hero in order to support his mother and himself.\n*'''Steven Minetta''' is twenty years old and was known as the \u201cbest dresser on the block\u201d when he was growing up.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|60}} He is eventually wounded but then returns to the platoon. At the conclusion of the novel, Minetta feels anger towards power figures and hopes to \u201cexpose the goddam Army.\u201d {{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|711}}\n*'''Dalleson''' was second in command to Cummings. He was very nervous throughout the novel and did not trust his own judgment. At the end of the novel, however, it is Dalleson who helps them win the war against the Japanese Army.\n\n==Themes==\n{{original research|section|date=August 2015}}\nThroughout the novel, Mailer dwells on many themes. These themes are recurring throughout his works and reappear in several of his later essays and novels.\n\n'''Dehumanization of soldiers''' Commenting on the dehumanization of soldiers in ''The Naked and the Dead,'' he said, \"The book finds man corrupted, confused to the point of helplessness, but it also find that there are limits beyond which he cannot be pushed.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lennon |first1=Michael |title=Norman Mailer: A Double Life |date=2014 |publisher=Simon & Shuster |location=New York |page=97}}</ref> The soldiers are continuously referred to as machines within the novel. At one point, the narrator describes this dehumanization stating, \u201cWhen a man was harnessed into a pack and web belt and carried a rifle and two bandoliers and several grenades, a bayonet and a helmet, he felt as if he had a tourniquet over both shoulders and across his chest. It was hard to breathe and his limbs kept falling asleep.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|24}} Thus, in this instance, the soldier is losing grasp of his bodily functions and simply going through the motions of being a \u201csoldier\u201d. \nDehumanization of the soldier is also seen in chapter 5 when the platoon had to carry antitank guns between 1st Battalion and A Company, which was about a mile of muddy trail. The men became numb and only went through the motions of carrying the guns. The generals disregarded the soldiers' exhaustion. This treatment of men as machines is reinforced throughout the novel. The expectation for the soldiers to fight off Japanese attacks despite their fear also demonstrates this dehumanization. The soldiers generally believed the army didn't see them as people and that \"they don't care if you live or die here [the infirmary]. All they want is to get you back where you can stop a bullet\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|chapter=The Naked and the Dead and Its Aftermath|pages=14\u201333|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|doi=10.2307/j.ctv6sj74q.5|isbn=978-1-61117-806-7|title=Understanding Norman Mailer|year=2017}}</ref>{{rp|354}} Meaning, when soldiers were injured, the Army didn't care about their well-being annd only cared that they would heal enough to go back out into warfare.\n\n'''Brotherhood:''' Another theme, brotherhood, is a positive feature in the novel. In feeling that they may not make it out alive, the soldiers developed strong friendships which are not relatable to people at home. Croft expresses his feelings of brotherhood and tells his comrades, \u201cYou\u2019re all good guys. You\u2019re all chicken, and you\u2019re all yellow, but you\u2019re good guys. They ain\u2019t a goddam thing wrong with you.\u201d, which is important to note considering Croft was the coldhearted character in the novel.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|202}} This idea of brotherhood is also seen within Part III when Brown, Goldstein, Ridges, and Stanley attempt to carry the wounded Wilson back to camp. Despite the physical strains of carrying Wilson back, the men presisted wanting to save Wilson. This brotherhood of the platoon is also illustrated in their reaction to the death of Hearn in comparison to the death of Roth. When Hearn, who was new to the platoon as the commander, was killed by Japanese soldiers, the platoon stood shocked for a couple of seconds and then tried to escape the fire of the Japanese. When Roth died however, \"the platoon was shattered. For ten minuted they huddled together on the shelf, too stricken, too terrified, to move on.<ref name=\":0\" />\"{{rp|684}} Roth had been with the platoon since the beginning and his death greatly effected all of the men, demonstrating the brotherhood they had with Roth and with each other.\n\n'''Loneliness:''' The theme of loneliness also reoccurs within the novel. Away from their family and friends at home, the soldiers are constantly lonely. The men in their ranks are of different social classes and religions, which sometimes makes it difficult for the men to find commonalities between one another. When they do share something in common, they see it as a unifying factor between them. For instance, Goldstein feels a connection and a sort of alliance with Roth since they are both Jewish. Although the men in the platoon do have a sense of brotherhood with one another, as mentioned above, they still feel alone during their deployment. Throughout the novel, the men also long for women and deeper friendships. Roth, for example, wishes to have someone whom he \u201ccould talk to seriously.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|51}} He realizes that he doesn\u2019t know his own comrades very well, since everyone he met when he initially entered the Army was either killed or reassigned somewhere else. The men also constantly degrade women, however, it is evident the absence of women caused them to feel lonelier and wish they were with them.\n\n'''Death and fear:''' Death and the fear of dying is another theme prevalent in the novel. The men are faced with unexpected deaths, such as Hennessey's, Wilson, Hearn, Roth, and Gallagher\u2019s wife who dies during childbirth. It is clear death surrounds them and their lives could be taken away in any moment. Cummings, having been surrounded by Army deaths the majority of his career, still never warms to the smell of rotting corpses. Red, like the other soldiers, realizes he or one of his comrades could be killed any minute. Even when they grew used to death and saw it as \"large and devastating and meaningless. Men who were killed were nearly men no longer around\", a comrade's death would cause \"the idea of death [to be] fresh and terrifying again\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|123}} This fear of death also had a negative impact on the mental health and sanity of the men. For instance, Red states, \"Goddam Army gets you so you're afraid to turn around\".{{rp|12}} The men began to have a pessimistic view of life believing \"All dead things... everything lives to die\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|228}} This was especially so since \"that's all [soldiers] can ever do in the Army, sit and think\" which caused the thoughts and fears of death to be constant and prevalent.<ref name=\":0\" /> {{rp|474}}\n\n'''Power:''' The theme of power is also in the novel through the power relations the men have with one another, especially those of high ranking with those below them. For instance, the theme is exemplified through General Cummings himself. Cummings compares himself to the \u201cchief monk\u201d and God throughout the book. He also openly supports the class system within the military, and states Hearn must accept the \u201cemotional prejudices of his class\u201d, especially since he is an officer. People of higher ranks like Hearn and Cummings, after all, enjoy a better quality of life than the other foot soldiers. They sleep in larger staterooms while the soldiers share small rooms and are jammed into cots. This power system and power relations is reinforced within the missions. After Hearn dies, Croft is \"relieved\" that there is no longer a rival to his power and takes over leading the platoon up the mountain.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|603}} While the other soldiers clearly want to stop and give up, they continue hiking the mountain simply because Croft commands them to. Chickenshit, as termed by [[Paul Fussell]] in \"Wartime: Understanding and Behavior in the Second World War\", was a major aspect of the theme of power in the novel.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=June 1991|title=Paul Fussell. <italic>Wartime: Understanding and Behavior in the Second World War</italic>. New York: Oxford University Press. 1989. Pp. x, 330. $19.95|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/96.3.843-a|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> This is shown in how Cummings makes Hearn do humiliating tasks and in the end sends him on a mission knowing he will die, which is the ultimate chickenshit since he sent him to die solely to demonstrate his power. This is another instance where the undemocratic nature of the Army is apparent.\n\n'''Homosexuality:''' The theme of homosexuality is most evident with Cummings. In his \"Time Machine\", Mailer illustrates Cummings growing up experiencing gender-role confusion. Although his mother supports Cummings' identity, his father refuses to have a son who is homosexual and thus sends him to military school. This portages the notion of the Army being only for \"real men\". However, there were a lot of homosexual men who were soldiers during WWII and as [[Allan B\u00e9rub\u00e9]] illustrates in ''Coming Out Under Fire: History of Gay Men and Women in World War Two'', they were often seen as trusted and respected soldiers and medics.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=June 1991|title=Allan Berube. <italic>Coming Out under Fire: The History of Gay Men and Women in World War Two</italic>. New York: Free Press. 1990. Pp. xiii, 377. $22.95|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/96.3.845|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> While in the Army, it is clear Cummings developed romantic feelings towards Hearn and sexually desired him. Through Cummings, Mailer illustrates his beliefs of homosexuality. Although Mailer believes being homosexual is evil, it is interesting he had the general be the homosexual character in the novel, especially since he depicts the general as being a powerful figure who is a good leader. Mailer also includes homosexual characters in his other works as well, such as in ''[[The Deer Park]].'' Mailer directly addresses this theme and his beliefs of homosexuality in \"The Homosexual Villain\" stating he saw homosexuals as evil and always depicted them as the villain in his works but realized they were humans.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mailer, Norman.|title=The homosexual villain|oclc=21704456}}</ref>\n\n'''Misogyny:''' The theme of misogyny also occurs within the novel. Like Mailer\u2019s other works, ''The Naked and the Dead'' constantly portrays women as sexual objects who are below men. Many men, especially Brown, fear their wives are cheating on them while they are at war. This only causes them to have more hatred towards women and a deep distrust towards them. Brown tells Stanley that if he finds out his wife cheated on him, he will beat her then throw her out.{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|168}} Later, in the Chorus \u201cWomen,\u201d Polack insists that \u201cthere ain\u2019t a fuggin woman is any good\u201d and Brown agrees. Women are especially emphasized within \"Time Machine\" segments. In these segments, the men\u2019s romantic relationships and sexual experiences are described in detail. In many of the \"Time Machines\", such as Martinez's, women are portrayed as simply sexual objects. In Croft's \"Time Machine\", we learn was cheated on by the women he loved which resulted in him being cold and having a hatred towards women. The men seem to disregard the fact that they have cheated several times on their partners but show extreme hatred in the thought of their wives cheating on them. The only character that seems to positively view his wife is Gallagher, who becomes miserable and lost after she dies. This deep hatred for women, however, is a way to mask how strongly these men miss and desire women; they desperately need women for a variety of different reasons.\n\n==Development==\n'''Writing development:''' Before he left for basic training, Mailer was certain that he could write \u201cTHE war novel\u201d based on his experiences as a cook and the experiences of soldiers in World War II.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Christopher |last=Beha |title=Does Mailer Matter? The Young Writer and the last literary celebrity |journal=Harper's Magazine |issue=88}}</ref>  After returning home from the war, he moved to France with his first wife, Beatrice, where he studied at the Sorbonne in [[Paris]].  Here, in just 15 months, Mailer wrote his war novel as noted in his introduction to its Fiftieth Anniversary Edition.<ref name=\"martinfrost.ws\">{{cite web|url=http://www.martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/jan2009/norman-mailer.html |title=Frost's Meditations |website=martinfrost.ws |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923062046/http://www.martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/jan2009/norman-mailer.html |archivedate=September 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nMailer states his writing inspiration came from the great Russian novelists like [[Leo Tolstoy]]. While writing, Mailer often read \u201cfrom [[Anna Karenina]] most mornings before he commenced his own work.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|7}} Mailer believed Tolstoy enabled him to bring compassion to his pages; Tolstoy taught him that \u201ccompassion is valueless without severity.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|8}} Mailer was convinced he brought this compassion to ''The Naked and the Dead'', and it is what enabled a 25-year-old to write an incredible war novel.\n\nThroughout his writing process, Mailer explained, he \u201cused to write twenty-five pages of first draft a week,\u201d which allowed his novel to flow from page to page.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.odysseyeditions.com/EBooks/Norman-Mailer/The-Naked-and-the-Dead/Author-commentary |title=The Naked and the Dead: Author commentary |first=Norman |last=Mailer |work=odysseyeditions.com |year=2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Mailer felt this novel was the easiest for him to write, as he finished it quickly and passionately. He later stated, \u201cPart of me thought it was possibly the greatest book written since [[War and Peace]].\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xi}}\n\nDespite the author\u2019s self-praise, he acknowledged his writing immaturity within the novel. Mailer insisted \u201cit was sloppily written in many parts (the words came too quickly and too easily) and there was hardly a noun in any sentence that was not holding hands with the nearest and most commonly available adjective.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xi}} However, despite this criticism, Mailer believed the book deserved to be a best seller. It was written with vigor and contained acute descriptiveness which enabled readers to imagine what World War II was really like. Mailer admitted that he still returned to ''The Naked and the Dead'' occasionally and reread passages because they gave him hope \u201cfor all of us.\u201d{{sfnp|Mailer|1948}}{{rp|xiii}}\n\n'''Character that represents Mailer:''' Mailer stated he did not portray himself as one of the characters. However, he mentions the character of Roth is the most similar to himself. He states Roth's experiences within the novel closely resembled his own experiences in WWII, especially in comparison to the other characters. This similarity is also evident in how they are both Jewish but don't necessarily strongly declare being Jewish.\n\n=== \"Fug\" ===\nThe publishers of ''The Naked and the Dead'' prevented Mailer from using the word \"fuck\" in his novel and had to use the [[euphemism]] \"fug\" instead. Mailer's version of a subsequent incident follows:\n               \n<blockquote>The word has been a source of great embarrassment to me over the years because, you know, Tallulah Bankhead's press agent, many years ago, got a story in the papers which went...\"Oh, hello, you're Norman Mailer,\" said Tallulah Bankhead allegedly, \"You're the young man that doesn't know how to spell...\" You know, the four-letter word was indicated with all sorts of asterisks.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lennon |first=Michael |last2=Mailer |first2=Norman |editor-last=Lennon |editor-first=J. Michael |year=1988 |chapter=1968 Panel Discussion, CBLT-TV, Toronto, moderated by Robert Fulford |title=Conversations with Norman Mailer |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=978-0878053513 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe incident is mentioned in [[John Green (author)|John Green]]'s ''[[An Abundance of Katherines]]''. Colin Singleton tells Lindsey Lee Wells he likes to read literary criticism after reading a book. Colin says the publisher indicated that no one in 1948 would buy ''The Naked and the Dead''  \"'because it contains even more F-bombs than it does Regular Bombs.' So Norman Mailer, as a kind of fug-you to the publisher, went through his 872-page book and changed every last F-word to 'fug.'\"  <ref>{{Citation |last=Green |first=John |pages=[https://archive.org/details/abundanceofkathe00gree/page/119 119\u2013120] |title=An Abundance of Katherines |year=2006 |publisher=Penguin Group |isbn=978-0-525-47688-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/abundanceofkathe00gree/page/119 }}</ref>\n\nThe rock band [[the Fugs]] took their name from this word.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefugs.com/history2.html|title=History of The Fugs|last1=Sanders|first1=Ed|website=The Fugs|publisher=Metze Publication Design|quote=[Tuli Kupferberg] was the one who came up with the name, the Fugs, borrowed from the euphemism in Normal [sic] Mailer's novel, The Naked and the Dead.}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Wikiquote|Norman Mailer#The Naked and the Dead|The Naked and the Dead}}\nIn 1948, at the age of twenty-five, Mailer published ''The Naked and the Dead,'' which was extremely successful. The book sold 200,000 copies in its first three months and remained on the ''New York Times'' best seller list for 62 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Lehmann-Hauptm |title=Norman Mailer, Towering Author with Matching Ego, Dies at 84 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=10 November 2007 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/10/books/11mailer.html?pagewanted=2&_r=1&hp&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1386183694-I%20VYF5Ha7SZvP1EE5Mp6KA& |url-access=subscription }}</ref>  Later, Modern Library named ''The Naked and the Dead'' one of the top hundred novels in the English language.<ref name=\"martinfrost.ws\"/>\n\nPublisher [[Bennett Cerf]] declared in 1948 \"only three novels published since the first of the year that were worth reading ... ''[[Cry, the Beloved Country]]'', ''[[The Ides of March (novel)|The Ides of March]]'', and ''The Naked and the Dead''.\"<ref name=\"rd\">{{cite news |title=Reader's digest: Gossip, news: J. F. Albright reports on A.B.A. meeting |title-link=American Booksellers Association |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |date=30 May 1948 |page=6 }}</ref>\n\nIn its initial review the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' complained that the novel \"grows increasingly unreadable\" due to Mailer's tendency to \"leave nothing out\".<ref>Ross, Alan. \"Under Fire.\" The Times Literary Supplement, 20 May 1949, p. 325.</ref> The ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' described the novel as \"dull\" for the same reason.<ref>Johnson, Pamela Hansford. \"New Fiction.\" Daily Telegraph, 13 May 1949, p. 6.</ref>\n\nLater, [[Gore Vidal]] would write:\n\n<blockquote>My first reaction to ''The Naked and the Dead'' was: it\u2019s a fake. A clever, talented, admirably executed fake. I have not changed my opinion of the book since\u2026 I do recall a fine description of men carrying a dying man down a mountain\u2026 Yet every time I got going in the narrative I would find myself stopped cold by a set of made-up, predictable characters taken not from life, but from the same novels all of us had read, and informed by a na\u00efvet\u00e9 which was at its worst when Mailer went into his Time-Machine and wrote those passages which resemble nothing so much as smudged carbons of a [[John Dos Passos|Dos Passos]] work.<ref>{{Citation |last=Vidal |first=Gore |authorlink=Gore Vidal |origyear=1960 |year=1993 |title=United States: Essays 1952\u20131992 |chapter=Norman Mailer\u2019s Self-Advertisements |publisher=Random House |location=New York |page=[https://archive.org/details/unitedstates00gore/page/32 32] |isbn=978-0-679-75572-2 |title-link=United States: Essays 1952\u20131992 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n;Bibliography\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Mailer |first=Norman |title=The Naked and the Dead |location=New York |publisher=Henry Holt & Company |year=1948 |edition=50th Anniversary }}\n\n{{Norman Mailer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naked and the Dead}}\n[[Category:1948 American novels]]\n[[Category:Rinehart & Company books]]\n[[Category:World War II novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Novels by Norman Mailer]]\n[[Category:Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Novels set on islands]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:1948 debut novels]]\n", "name_user": "LillianSpell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThemes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Naked_and_the_Dead"}
{"title_page": "Cannon Street station", "text_new": "{{for|other stations with the same name}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{short description|London railway and Underground station}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Cannon Street\n| alt_name      = London Cannon Street\n| manager       = [[Network Rail]]\n| owner         =\n| locale        = [[Cannon Street]]\n| borough       = [[City of London]]\n| platforms     = 7\n| fare_zone     = 1\n| railcode      = CST\n| railcode2     =\n| dft_category  = A\n| image_name    = Cannon Street station new building.JPG\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Main entrance\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.5104|-0.0907|type:railwaystation_region:GB-LND|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type      = Central London\n| years1        = 1 September 1866\n| years2        = 5 June 1926\n| years3        = 28 June 1926\n| years4        = 5 August 1974\n| years5        = 9 September 1974\n| events1       = Opened\n| events2       = Closed\n| events3       = Reopened\n| events4       = Closed\n| events5       = Reopened\n<!--| railexits0203 =\n| railexits0304 =\n| railexits0405 = {{increase}} 17.460\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 17.614\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 21.106\n| railexits0708 = {{increase}} 22.177\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 21.646\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 20.229\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 20.528\n| railexits1112 = {{decrease}} 20.223\n| railexits1213 = {{decrease}} 20.020\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 20.689 -->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 22.130\n| railexits1516 = {{decrease}} 21.242{{efn|This decrease was caused by a change in methodology which reduced usage figures at Cannon Street by 1.913 million. Without the changes, the usage would have been 23.155 million.}}\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 22.660\n| railexits1718 = {{increase}} 23.447\n| railexits1819 = {{decrease}} 20.615\n<!-- Interchange numbers should not be displayed as per consensus in the talk page discussion (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template_talk:Infobox_GB_station#Interchange_statistics,_2018); the number falls well below 10% of total entries/exits.\n| railint0203   =\n| railint0304   =\n| railint0405   =\n| railint0506   =\n| railint0607   =\n| railint0708   =\n| railint0809   =\n| railint0910   =\n| railint1011   =\n| railint1112   = {{pad|2em}}0.440\n| railint1213   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.437\n| railint1314   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 0.465\n| raillowint1415 = {{pad|2em}} ''not available''  the published figure of 2,350,974 seems unlikely\n| railint1516   = {{pad|2em}} 0.767\n| railint1617   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.714\n| railint1718   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.290 -->\n| interchange   = [[Bank\u2013Monument station|Bank]] {{rail-interchange|london|underground}} {{rail-interchange|london|dlr}}\n| interchange_note =<ref>{{Citation London station interchange February 2019}}</ref>\n| imagesize        = x240px\n| symbol           = rail\n| gridref          = TQ326808\n| original         = [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]]\n| pregroup         = [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]]\n| postgroup        = [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]]\n| access           = yes\n}}\n'''Cannon Street station''', also known as '''London Cannon Street''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CST/details.html |title=Station facilities for London Cannon Street |work=National Rail Enquiries |accessdate=29 May 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612010452/http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CST/details.html |archivedate=12 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a [[London station group|central London railway terminus]] and connected [[London Underground]] station in [[List of stations in London fare zone 1|Travelcard zone 1]] located on [[Cannon Street]] in the [[City of London]] and managed by [[Network Rail]]. It is one of two London termini of the [[South Eastern main line]], the other being {{rws|Charing Cross}}, while the Underground station is on the [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] and [[District line]]s, between [[Bank and Monument stations|Monument]] and [[Mansion House tube station|Mansion House]]. The station runs services by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]], mostly catering for commuters in southeast London and Kent, with occasional services further into the latter.\n\nThe station was built on a site of the medieval [[steelyard]], the trading base in England of the [[Hanseatic League]]. It was built by the [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]] in order to have a railway terminal in the City and compete with the rival [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]]. This required a new bridge across the [[River Thames]], which was constructed between 1863 and 1866. The station was initially a stop for continental services from Charing Cross, and that route was convenient for travel between the City and the [[West End of London|West End]], until the construction of the [[District Railway]]. It remained popular with commuters, though its off-peak services were discontinued in the early 20th century, leading to it being closed on Sundays for almost 100 years. The original hotel on the station was unsuccessful, and eventually closed. The station was controversially renovated in the late 1950s by [[John Poulson]], while further construction on top of the station building occurred during the City's 1980s property boom. The Poulson building was replaced in 2007 as part of a general renovation of the station to make it more accessible. As part of the [[Thameslink Programme]] development in the 2010s, it was re-opened on Sundays and began to offer more long-distance services in place of Charing Cross.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Cannon street railway bridge 2.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|Cannon Street Railway Bridge, 2005]]\nCannon Street is a terminal station, approached across the [[River Thames]] by the Cannon Street Railway Bridge. Its approach by rail is through a triangular connection to both {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} and {{stnlnk|Charing Cross}}. It is one of eighteen stations in the country that are managed by [[Network Rail]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our stations |url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/communities/passengers/our-stations/ |website=NetworkRail |accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere were originally eight platforms; a refurbishment in the late 1990s removed the original platform 1.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} It has entrances on [[Cannon Street]] itself and Dowgate Hill. It is located near [[London Stone]] (to the north of the station).\n\n[[London Buses]] routes [[London Buses route 15|15]], [[London Buses route 17|17]], [[London Buses route 521|521]] and heritage route [[London Buses route 15 (Heritage)|15H]] and night routes [[London Buses route N15|N15]] and [[List of night buses in London#N199|N199]] serve the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.tfl.gov.uk/bus-route-maps/central-london-bus-map.pdf |title=Central London Bus Map |publisher=Transport for London |accessdate=17 July 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313082004/http://content.tfl.gov.uk/bus-route-maps/central-london-bus-map.pdf |archivedate=13 March 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Original structure===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station.jpg|thumb|left|Front of original station building, c. 1910]]\nCannon Street station was built on a site where the [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic]] merchants' steelyard had been based from the 10th century until 1598.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=127}} The site was proposed in 1860 by the [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]] (SER) in response to its rival, the [[London, Chatham & Dover Railway]] (LC&DR), extending a line into the [[City of London]] as far north as [[Ludgate Hill]]. The SER had already made plans to extend its line towards {{rws|Charing Cross}}, but decided that it should complement this with a terminus in the City.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=172}}\n\nIn 1861, the company obtained an act for a station in Cannon Street, a short distance from [[Mansion House, London|Mansion House]] and the [[Bank of England]].{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=172}} In addition to taking traffic from the LC&DR, the new station would provide a direct railway link between the City and the [[West End of London|West End]], over which a journey could be made in a fraction of the time taken travelling by road.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=114}} The approach was a {{convert|60|chain|adj=on}} branch of the line to Charing Cross, west of London Bridge. Work started on the station and its approach in July 1863.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}}\n\nThe station was opened on 1 September 1866{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}} at a cost of \u00a34 million (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|4|1866}} million).{{sfn|Ball|Sunderland|2002|p=214}} The original building was designed by [[John Hawkshaw|Sir John Hawkshaw]] and [[John Wolfe-Barry]] and was characterised by its two [[Christopher Wren]]-style towers, {{convert|23|ft|m|abbr=on}} square and {{convert|135|ft|m|abbr=on}} high, which faced on to the [[River Thames]]. The towers supported an iron train shed, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and crowned by a high single arch, almost semicircular, of glass and iron. The station is carried over [[Thames Street, London|Upper Thames Street]] on a brick viaduct, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and containing 27 million bricks.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2009|p=69}} Below this viaduct exist the remains of a number of Roman buildings, which form a [[scheduled ancient monument]].{{sfn|Allinson|Thornton|2014|p=58}} The bridge was open to pedestrians between 1872 and 1877; they paid a toll of [[Halfpenny (British pre-decimal coin)|\u00bdd]].{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}}\n\n[[File:Cannon Street Station 2.jpg|thumb|left|Original station viewed from the railway bridge, c. 1910]]\nThe five-storey City Terminus Hotel, which fronted the station, was opened in May 1867. It was an [[Italianate]] style hotel and forecourt, designed by [[Edward Middleton Barry|E. M. Barry]], and it provided many of the station's passenger facilities, as well as an appropriate architectural frontispiece to the street. This arrangement was very similar to that put in place at Charing Cross.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} The hotel was not profitable, and was over \u00a347,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|47000|1870|fmt=c|r=-3}}) in debt by 1870.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=120}} The City Terminus Hotel was renamed the Cannon Street Hotel in 1879.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} In July 1920, the hotel was the first meeting point of the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]]. Most of the hotel was closed in 1931, but the public rooms were kept open for meetings. The rest were converted into offices and renamed Southern House.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} The hotel is referred to in The Fire Sermon section of [[T. S. Eliot]]'s ''[[The Waste Land]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/47311/the-waste-land |title=The Waste Land by T. S. Eliot |first=Poetry |last=Foundation |date=15 May 2019 |website=Poetry Foundation}}</ref>\n\nUpon its opening Cannon Street station was a stopping point for all services to and from Charing Cross, including boat trains to Continental Europe. A shuttle service between the two stations ran every 20 minutes and became a popular way of travelling between the City and the West End.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} However, the opening of the [[District Railway]] as far as [[Blackfriars tube station|Blackfriars]] caused traffic to decline, and its extension to [[Mansion House tube station|Mansion House]] the following year reduced it further. The SER's route could not compete with the Underground, which was more direct and reliable,{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=176}} but suburban traffic to Cannon Street remained popular, and the bridge was widened to {{convert|120|ft}} in the late 1880s, allowing ten tracks with sidings. The rebuilt bridge was opened on 13 February 1892.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=177}} The signal boxes outside the station were upgraded the following year.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=124}}\n\nThe [[London and Southwestern Railway]] (LSWR) became interested in using Cannon Street as a terminus, as it would allow a connection between [[London Waterloo railway station|Waterloo]] and the City.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=119}}\n\n===War years===\nWork on strengthening the bridge, by the addition of six new {{convert|443|ft|adj=on}} girders in between the existing ones, was completed in 1913.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=177}}\n\nMost Cannon Street train services ceased during [[World War I]]. Continental boat trains were stopped on 15 November 1914 and rerouted to Victoria. The station stopped being served by through services from Charing Cross on 31 December 1916, and was closed on Sundays. Services were reduced further on 1 May 1918, when it was closed after 3&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays and between 11&nbsp;a.m. and 4&nbsp;p.m. Mondays to Fridays. This allowed Cannon Street to be used as a goods depot for war supplies.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|pp=177\u2013178}}\n\nBetween 5 and 28 June 1926, the station was closed to allow the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]] to carry out various works, including the rebuilding of the platforms, relaying of the tracks and installation of a new system of electrical signalling \u2013 the four-aspect colour light scheme. The station was also renovated and the glass roof cleaned. The number of platforms was reduced from nine to eight, with five set aside for the new electric trains. The signal box spanning the width of the railway bridge was removed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannon Street Station Reopened |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=29 June 1926 |p=8 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS135469789&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In July 1939, Cannon Street was closed for a week following a fire in [[Borough Market]] which prevented any trains accessing it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannon Street Station Reopened |newspaper=The Times |date=25 July 1939 |p=9 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS153040121&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe station, which had been subject to structural neglect prior to [[World War II]], suffered extensive bomb damage and was hit by several incendiary devices which damaged the roof. A high explosive also hit platform 8.<ref>{{cite news |title=London Termini Bomb Damage |newspaper=The Times |date=19 November 1943 |p=8 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS136265075&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The original glass roof had been removed before the war, in an attempt to save it; however, the factory in which the roof was stored was itself badly bombed, destroying the roof.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}}\n\n===Redevelopment===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station (8417710796).jpg|thumb|upright|Cannon Street station in 1969, showing the easterly of the twin towers]]\nFollowing [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1948\u20131994#The 1940s: Nationalisation|nationalisation of the railways]] in 1948, the station was managed by the [[Southern Region of British Railways]]. The station's prime location coupled with the property boom of the 1950s and the need for [[British Rail]] to seek alternative revenue streams made war-damaged Cannon Street a key target for property developers.<ref name=times55/> Steam trains stopped running from Cannon Street in 1959.{{sfn|Davies|Grant|1983|p=47}}\n\nVarious plans were mooted for the reconstruction of the station, from the installation of a new ticket hall and concourse under Southern House in 1955 as part of British Rail's [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1948\u20131994#The Modernisation Plan|Modernisation Plan]] to the construction of a car park estimated to cost \u00a3125,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|125000|1955|fmt=c|r=-3}})<ref name=times55>{{cite news |title=Rebuilding of Cannon Street Station |newspaper=The Times |date=17 November 1955 |p=15 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS252269937&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and even a helipad.{{efn|The preferred site was the old [[Nine Elms]] goods yard in [[Battersea]]}}<ref>{{cite news |title=First Choice for Helicopter Site |work=The Times |date=3 March 1962 |p=6 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS102851171&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1962, the [[British Transport Commission]] entered into an agreement with Town & Country Properties for the construction of a multi-storey office building above the station with {{convert|154000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of floor space. The cost of the development was \u00a32.35&nbsp;million (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|2.35|1965}} million) and it was scheduled for completion by June 1965.<ref>{{cite news |title=Big New Buildings Over Two London Termini |newspaper=The Times |date=22 March 1962 |p=12 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS203645558&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for redevelopment, the remains of the train shed roof had been demolished in 1958, and Barry's hotel (which had been used as offices since 1931) soon followed in 1960.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=128}} The architect selected to design the new building was [[John Poulson]] who was good friends with Graham Tunbridge, a British Rail surveyor whom he had met during the war. Poulson took advantage of this friendship to win contracts for the redevelopment of various British Rail termini. He paid Tunbridge a weekly income of \u00a325 and received in return building contracts, including the rebuilding of [[London Waterloo station|Waterloo]] and [[East Croydon station]]s. At his trial in 1974, Poulson admitted that, shortly before receiving the Cannon Street building contract, he had given Tunbridge a cheque for \u00a3200 and a suit worth \u00a380.<ref>{{cite news |title=John Poulson tells of gifts to rail man |newspaper=The Times |date=15 January 1974|p=4|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS68254255&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Poulson was later found guilty of corruption charges and given a seven-year concurrent sentence; Tunbridge received a 15-month suspended sentence and a \u00a34,000 fine for his role in the affair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seven-year concurrent sentence on Mr Poulson|newspaper=The Times|date=16 March 1974 |p=3|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS50559600&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAll that now remains of the original station architecture are the twin {{convert|120|ft|m|abbr=on}} yellow brick towers at the country-end and parts of the low flanking walls.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}}\n\n===Modern era===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station 3.jpg|thumb|right|[[John Poulson]]'s office block in 2007 prior to redevelopment]]\nThe station's twin brick towers were [[listed building|listed Grade II]] in 1972.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1192326 |desc=Pair of Towers at Cannon Street Station: Western Tower to Cannon Street Station |grade=II |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1359145 |desc=Eastern Tower to Cannon Street Station: Pair of Towers at Cannon Street Station |grade=II |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1974, the station was closed for five weeks from 2 August to 9 September to enable alterations to be made to the track and the approaches to London Bridge to be resignalled. Traffic was diverted to London Bridge, Charing Cross and {{LUL stations|station=Blackfriars}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street station closing for five weeks|newspaper=The Times|date=29 July 1974|p=3|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS51477245&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 March 1976, a [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) bomb of about 10&nbsp;lb (4.5&nbsp;kg) exploded on an empty commuter train leaving Cannon Street, injuring eight people on another train travelling alongside.{{efn|Had the bomb exploded 13 minutes earlier it would have caused widespread carnage as the train had been carrying hundreds of commuters on a service from [[Sevenoaks railway station|Sevenoaks]].<ref name=sevenoaks/>}}<ref name=sevenoaks>{{cite news|title=Thirteen minutes saved hundreds on the 7.49 from Sevenoaks|work=The Times|date=5 March 1976|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS33783397&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 1984, it was reported in ''[[The Times]]'' that Cannon Street was to close. At the time, the station had been closed for weekends and evenings, and the publication of British Rail's new timetable for 1984\u20131985 revealed that it would lose all its direct off-peak services to the south-east. Services from Sevenoaks, {{stnlnk|Orpington}}, {{stnlnk|Hayes}}, {{stnlnk|Dartford}}, {{stnlnk|Sidcup}}, {{stnlnk|Bexleyheath}}, {{stnlnk|Woolwich}}, [[Lewisham station|Lewisham]] and [[Greenwich station|Greenwich]] would instead terminate at {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} except during peak hours.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street rail station 'near to closure'|newspaper=The Times|date=15 February 1984|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS34180687&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> This was denied by British Rail (Southern)'s manager David Kirby, who pointed out that it had invested \u00a310&nbsp;million in redecking the railway bridge, and that passengers travelling from the south-east during off-peak hours would most likely be visiting the [[West End of London|West End]] and not [[City of London|the City]].<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Kirby|title=Cannon Street Station|newspaper=The Times|date=22 February 1984|p=15|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=&docId=CS252939862&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, the twin towers were restored in a project costing \u00a3242,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|242000|1972|fmt=c|r=-3}}). The works revealed that the east tower still contained a large water tank which was used during the days of steam traction to replenish locomotives and to power the station's hydraulic systems. The brickwork was repaired, cleaned and repointed, and the [[weather vane]]s gilded to complement the dome of nearby [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. This work was one of the Railway Heritage Trust's first projects and coincided with an exhibition held in the station in August of the same year to mark its 150th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Restoration at Cannon Street|newspaper=The Times|date=2 December 1985|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS34312578&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plumber's Apprentice.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The ''Plumber's Apprentice'' by [[Martin Jennings]], unveiled in 2011 to mark the 400th anniversary of the [[Worshipful Company of Plumbers]] whose Guild Hall was demolished to make way for the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/plumber-s-apprentice-statue |title=Statue: Plumber's Apprentice statue |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=London Remembers |access-date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408005949/http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/plumber-s-apprentice-statue |archivedate=8 April 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nIn the 1980s, there was another property boom and British Rail again began looking into further commercial uses of the Cannon Street landspace, including {{convert|500000|sqft}} of office space.<ref>{{cite news|first=Judith|last=Hutley|title=BR names Cannon St shortlist|newspaper=The Times|date=17 March 1986|p=20|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF500456800&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[air rights]] over the platforms to the rear of Poulson's office were sold to Speyhawk which appointed [[Bovis Construction]] to build a free-standing structure comprising two office blocks on a 6,000 tonne steel deck constructed over the station's eight platforms.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} The Cannons Club, a sports club, was founded beneath the station's arches around this time, and quickly became one of the most prestigious [[squash (sport)|squash]] clubs in the country. [[InterCity]], the high-speed arm of British Rail, subsequently sponsored the National Squash Championships and National Squash Challenge.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colin|last=McQuillan|title=Branching out with more support|newspaper=The Times|date=17 September 1986|p=37|accessdate=18 July 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF501698917&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe larger office block, the \"Atrium building\", provides {{convert|190000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space on six floors and is linked to the smaller building, the \"River building\", via a glazed link raised through a central glazed atrium. The River building, which has two storeys, is built on the steel deck and contained within the station's two flank walls, which were rebuilt, providing {{convert|95000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space. This building projects slightly beyond the restored twin towers which form the riverside boundary to the development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Construction Contracts: Building Over Busy Station|work=Financial Times|date=6 March 1989}}</ref> The Atrium building was later let to the [[London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange|London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange (Liffe)]]. The River building has a {{convert|1|acre|ha}} roof garden. The project cost around \u00a3500,000 and was laid to comply with planning restrictions which required the building to be low and flat to maintain the sight lines from St Paul's to [[Tower Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=City garden feels the frost|work=The Times|date=27 November 1991|p=40|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF501903210&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nPlanning permission was granted in March 2007 to replace the Poulson building, with a new air rights building designed by Foggo Associates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/dailynews/foggo_wins_green_light_for_cannon_street_station_redesign.html|title=Foggo Wins Green Light for Cannon Street Station Redesign|publisher=Architects Journal|date=21 March 2007}}</ref> [[Gerald D. Hines|Hines]], the US developer, led a \u00a3360&nbsp;million project involving the demolition of Poulson's office block, replacing it with a mixed-use development containing more than {{convert|400000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space alongside {{convert|17000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of station retail space.{{sfn|Allinson|Thornton|2014|p=58}} The redevelopment was part of a larger regeneration programme undertaken by [[Network Rail]] to modernise and \"unlock the commercial potential\" of the main London termini; {{stnlnk|Euston}} and {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} were also redeveloped. Network Rail's director of commercial property said that the finished station would be \"less congested and more accessible for passengers.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street to lead revamp of stations|newspaper=The Times|date=6 April 2007|p=55|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF503522467&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Cannon Street won the award for \"Major Station of the Year\" at the 2013 National Rail Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Boom time for Cannon Street station |first=Paul |last=Prentice |magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]] |date=27 November 2013 |issue=736 |pages=48\u201353 |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the station's opening hours were extended to 0500\u20130100 Monday to Sunday (prior to this, the station had been closed on Sundays and during the evenings), and several services which previously terminated at Charing Cross were diverted to Cannon Street as a result of [[Thameslink Programme]] works. Some of these services will revert to terminating at Charing Cross following the completion of the works, while services from the [[Greenwich line]] and from [[New Cross railway station|New Cross]] and [[St Johns railway station|St Johns]] will permanently run to Cannon Street due to the removal of the Spa Road Junction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southernrailway.com/download/32760/january-impacts/|title=Impacts and Travel Advice|publisher=Southern Railway|date=January 2015|accessdate=18 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420133712/http://www.southernrailway.com/download/32760/january-impacts/|archivedate=20 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/news/four-weeks-to-go-before-cross-london-thameslink-trains-stop-calling-at-london-bridge-rail-station|title=Four Weeks To Go Before Cross-London Thameslink Trains Stop Calling At London Bridge|work=Network Rail News|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==National Rail==\n[[File:Cannon Street 2020.jpg|thumb|right|The station viewed from the south bank of the Thames, 2020]]\nThe station connects the south side of the City to south and south-east London via {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} station. Some services run directly into Cannon Street from [[Kent]] and [[East Sussex]], but only during rush hours. Occasionally during the weekends when track maintenance is in progress, the station serves as an intermediate station between London Bridge and {{stnlnk|Charing Cross}}. Either trains reverse at the station or rail passengers change trains here. From 1918 to 2015, the station was closed on Sundays; this changed with Southeastern's introduction of a new timetable from January 2015 which resulted in the station's opening hours being extended over the entire week,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teamlondonbridge.co.uk/newsdetails.aspx?ref=2889 |title=Southeastern consults on changes to timetable in December 2014 |work=Team London Bridge |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003061510/http://www.teamlondonbridge.co.uk/newsdetails.aspx?ref=2889 |archivedate=3 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> except when engineering works require its closure and services are diverted to Charing Cross.<ref>{{cite news |last=Collier |first=Hatty |url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/12898684.London_Bridge_and_Cannon_Street_closed_to_Southeastern_passengers_on_Sunday/ |title=London Bridge and Cannon Street closed to Southeastern passengers on Sunday |work=[[News Shopper]] |date=18 April 2015 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150809032049/http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/12898684.London_Bridge_and_Cannon_Street_closed_to_Southeastern_passengers_on_Sunday/ |archivedate=9 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Services===\nThe typical off-peak service from the station is:<ref name=tt>{{cite web|url=https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/travel-information/more-travel-help/station-information/stations/london-cannon-street|title=Timetables for London Cannon Street|publisher=Southeastern|id=Select an individual timetable to verify the service information|accessdate=19 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719120708/https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/travel-information/more-travel-help/station-information/stations/london-cannon-street|archivedate=19 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n* 2&nbsp;trains per hour (tph) \u2013 {{Stnlnk|Hayes}} via [[Lewisham station|Lewisham]]\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 {{Stnlnk|Orpington}} via {{Stnlnk|Grove Park}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Greenwich and [[Woolwich Arsenal station|Woolwich Arsenal]] to {{stnlnk|Slade Green}} then return via {{Stnlnk|Sidcup}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Greenwich and Woolwich Arsenal to Slade Green then return via {{Stnlnk|Barnehurst}} and {{Stnlnk|Bexleyheath}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Bexleyheath to Barnehurst, then return via Woolwich Arsenal and Greenwich\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Sidcup to {{Stnlnk|Crayford}}, then return via [[Woolwich Arsenal station|Woolwich Arsenal]] and {{stnlnk|Greenwich}}\n\nDuring peak hours, there are also services to Hastings, Tunbridge Wells, Ore and to Ramsgate or Broadstairs via Chatham.<ref name=tt/>\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|previous={{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}}|route=[[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]<br><small>[[South Eastern main line]]|next=|col={{SE color}}}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n===Accidents and incidents===\n*On 26 December 1867, seven passengers and three train crew members were injured when, \"during a very thick fog\", a train arriving at Cannon Street from [[Greenwich station|Greenwich]] collided with another from [[London Waterloo station|Waterloo]] due to a signaller's error.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=2888|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 26th December 1867 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 27 June 1914, one person was killed and 20 were injured in a collision and subsequent derailment at Cannon Street. A train departing for {{rws|Hastings}} was in a side-long collision with a train arriving, across its path, from {{rws|Plumstead}} and, although the collision occurred at low speed, part of the Plumstead service was derailed and one of its carriages overturned. The driver of the Plumstead service was blamed for a failure to observe, and a misreading of, signals which took his train into the path of the Hastings-bound service. An investigation found the man who died was likely leaning out of the window at the moment his carriage overturned, and he might have avoided serious injury had he been seated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=407|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 27th June 1914 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 16 July 1919, 75 people were injured or left shaken when a train arriving from {{rws|Dartford}} hit the buffers at the end of Cannon Street's platform seven. Twelve of the injured required hospital treatment. A [[Board of Trade]] report into the incident blamed \"an error of judgment\" on the driver's part while he was braking on his approach to the platform end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/docsummary.php?docID=2278|title=Accident Returns: Extract for the Accident at Cannon Street on 16th July 1919 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 11 May 1941, the station was bombed in a [[Luftwaffe]] air raid. At least one locomotive was severely damaged.<ref name=Earnshaw8>{{cite book |last=Earnshaw |first=Alan |title=Trains in Trouble: Vol. 8 |year=1993 |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=Penryn |isbn=0-906899-52-4 |page=20 }}</ref>\n*On 20 March 1951, a [[diesel electric multiple unit]] and an [[electric multiple unit]] were in a side-long collision when the driver of the latter misread signals.<ref name=Earnshaw5>{{cite book |last=Earnshaw |first=Alan |title=Trains in Trouble: Vol. 5 |year=1989 |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=Penryn |isbn=0-906899-35-4 |pages=40\u201341 }}</ref>\n*On 5 April 1957, the signal box was destroyed by a fire due to an electrical fault. The station was consequently put out of action. Using hand signals, a skeleton service was put in place on 8 April. A temporary signal box was erected which came into operation on 5 May. Steam locomotives were temporarily banned from using the station, with [[British Rail Class 201|Hastings Units]] being introduced into service earlier than planned. A full service was resumed from 6 May. Construction of a new signal box began on 19 April and it came into service on 16 December.<ref name=Glover>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric |first=John |last=Glover |publisher=Ian Allan |location=Hersham |year=2001 |pages=138\u201339 |isbn=0-7110-2807-9}}</ref>\n*On 20 March 1961, a side-long collision and partial derailment resulted in injury to 12 people aboard an arriving service whose driver inadvertently passed a red signal and ran into an empty train as it left Cannon Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=410|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 20th March 1961 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 4 March 1976, [[Cannon Street train bombing|a bomb exploded]] on an empty electric multiple unit at the station. Eight people in an adjacent train were injured.<ref name=Moody>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric 1909\u20131979 |first=G. T. |last=Moody |origyear=1957 |year=1979 |edition=Fifth |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd |location=Shepperton |page=231 |isbn=0-7110-0924-4}}</ref>\n* On 20 August 1989, the [[Marchioness disaster|''Marchioness'' pleasure boat sank]] close to Cannon Street Railway Bridge, killing 51 people.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=124}}\n*On 8 January 1991, [[Cannon Street station rail crash|two people were killed and hundreds were injured]] when an electric multiple unit failed to stop on a dead-end platform and collided with the buffers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|title=On this Day : 8 January 1991: One dead as train crashes into buffers|work=BBC News|accessdate=17 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108160834/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|archivedate=8 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==London Underground==\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Cannon Street|symbol=underground\n| alt_name      =\n| manager       = [[London Underground]]\n| manager1      =\n| manager2      =\n| owner         =\n| owner1        =\n| owner2        =\n| locale        = [[Cannon Street]]\n| borough       = [[City of London]]\n| platforms     = 2\n| fare_zone     = 1\n| fare_zone_1   =\n| image_name    = Cannon Street tube stn entrance 2012.JPG\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Entrance from Dowgate Hill\n| coordinates   = \n| map_type      =\n| years1        = 1884\n| years2        = \n| years3        =\n| events1       = Opened (MICCR)\n| events2       =\n| events3       =\n<!--| tubeexits03   =\n| tubeexits04   = {{increase}} 4.096\n| tubeexits05   =\n| tubeexits06   = 4.325\n| tubeexits07   = {{decrease}} 4.11\n| tubeexits08   = {{increase}} 4.54\n| tubeexits09   = {{decrease}} 3.933-->\n| access = yes\n| access_note = (Westbound only)<ref>{{citation step free tube map}}</ref>\n}}\nThe London Underground station is sub-surface, situated immediately below the main line station. It is served by the [[District line|District]] and [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle line]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|title=Standard Tube Map|publisher=Transport for London|accessdate=19 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625083557/http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Entrances are located on Cannon Street, Dowgate Hill, and on the main line concourse upstairs at the National Rail station, providing an interconnection for commuters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@51.5115103,-0.0908027,3a,75y,79.66h,83.74t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sEFgTBF1MFT_tj2iqWBZ-ww!2e0!7i13312!8i6656|title=Cannon Street Underground Station|publisher=Google Maps|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> An [[out of station interchange]] with [[Bank and Monument stations|Bank station]] has been running since 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citymetric.com/transport/london-s-tube-map-needs-rethink-how-it-shows-bankmonument-interchange-4425|title=London's Tube Map needs to rethink how it shows Bank / Monument interchange|work=City Metric|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===History===\nBy 1876, the [[Metropolitan Railway]] (MR) and [[District Railway]] (DR) had constructed the majority of the Inner Circle (now the Circle line), reaching {{LUL stations|station=Aldgate}} and {{LUL stations|station=Mansion House}} respectively.{{sfn|Day|Reed|2008|pp=255\u2013256}} The companies were in dispute over the completion of the route as the DR was struggling financially and the MR was concerned that completion would affect its revenues through increased competition from the DR in the City area. In 1874, city financiers who were keen to see the line completed established the Metropolitan Inner Circle Completion Railway (MICCR) to link Mansion House to Aldgate.{{sfn|Brandon|2013|p=58}}{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=64}} Forced into action, the MR bought out the company, and it and the DR began construction of the final section of the Inner Circle in 1879.{{sfn|Brandon|2013|p=58}}\n\nOn 6 October 1884, the final section of the Inner Circle was opened, along with Cannon Street station.{{sfn|Lee|1956|p=47}} Initially, the station was served by trains of both companies as part of the circular Inner Circle service, but various operational patterns have been used during the station's life.{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=65}} The Inner Circle service achieved a separate identity as the Circle line in 1949, although its trains were still provided by the District or Metropolitan lines.{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=66}}\n\nA station here was part of the abandoned phase two expansion of the Fleet line (now [[Jubilee line]]). It had originally been planned in 1943, and was revived as a major transport plan in 1965.{{sfn|Mitchell|2003|p=1}} London Transport spent \u00a310m (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|10|1972}}m) in 1972 safeguarding the route underneath Cannon Street and building reinforcements for laying a tube in the water-bearing ground around the station. The plan was abandoned in the early 1980s in favour of the current extension further south.{{sfn|Mitchell|2003|p=3-4}}\n\nThe Underground station underwent major reconstruction at the same time as the main line station, with the work being completed in 2012. From 14 December 2014, the station's opening hours changed significantly, with the station opening on Sundays and no longer closing early in the evenings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenorthbank.org/northbank-news/increased-service-of-district-line-trains-from-14th-dec/|title=Increased Services of District Line Trains from 14 Dec|work=Northbank News|accessdate=19 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404130041/https://www.thenorthbank.org/northbank-news/increased-service-of-district-line-trains-from-14th-dec/|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station previously had restricted opening hours because it primarily served the local financial services sector, so there was low demand for services outside office hours. However, with the main line station's opening hours being extended due to the [[Thameslink Programme]], the Underground station's opening hours were changed to accommodate the additional passengers.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{s-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Circle|previous=Mansion House|next=Monument|type=Victoria|type2=Tower Hill}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=District|previous=Mansion House|next=Monument|type=Three}}\n{{s-note|text=Abandoned plans}}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Jubilee|previous=Ludgate Circus|next=Fenchurch Street|type2=Phases2&3|notemid=Phase 2 (never constructed)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin|25em}}\n* {{cite book |last=Allinson|first=Ken|last2=Thornton|first2=Victoria|title=London's Contemporary Architecture: An Explorer's Guide|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=978-1-317-69046-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ball|first=Michael|last2=Sunderland|first2=David|title=An Economic History of London 1800\u20131914|year=2002|isbn=978-1-134-54030-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Brandon|first=David|title=London And The Victorian Railway|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2013|isbn=978-1-445-62926-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Christopher|first=John|title=London's Historic Railway Stations Through Time|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2015|isbn=978-1-445-65111-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Day |first1=John R. |last2=Reed |first2=John |title=The Story of London's Underground |edition=10th |year=2008 |origyear=1963 |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=978-1-85414-316-7 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Davies|first1=R.|last2=Grant|first2=M.D.|title=London and its Railways|publisher=David & Charles|year=1983|isbn=0-7153-8107-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gray|first=Adrian|title=South Eastern Railway|publisher=Middleton Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0-906520-85-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jackson|first=Alan| year = 1984 |origyear=1969 | title = London's Termini | publisher = David & Charles | edition=New Revised| isbn = 0-330-02747-6|location=London|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lee|first=Charles Edward|title=The Metropolitan District Railway|publisher=Oakwood Press|year=1956|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Martin|first=Andrew|title=Underground, Overground: A Passenger's History of the Tube|publisher=Profile Books|year=2012|isbn=978-1-847-65807-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=McCarthy |first1=Colin |last2=McCarthy |first2=David |title = Railways of Britain \u2013 London North of the Thames |publisher = Ian Allan Publishing |location= Hersham, Surrey |isbn=978-0-7110-3346-7 |year=2009 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Mitchell|first=Bob|title=Jubilee Line Extension: From Concept to Completion|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=2003|isbn=978-0-727-73028-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Weinreb|first=Ben|last2=Hibbert|first2=Christopher|last3=Keay|first3=Julia|last4=Keay|first4=John|title=The London Encyclopedia|publisher=Pan MacMillan|year=2008|isbn=978-1-4050-4924-5|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cannon Street station}}\n* [https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/collections/collections-online/photographs/ London Transport Museum Photographic Archive]\n**{{ltmcollection|49/9889749.jpg|Underground station, 1896}}\n**{{ltmcollection|61/9889861.jpg|Underground station and Cannon Street Hotel, 1916}}\n**{{ltmcollection|70/9872970.jpg|Booking hall, 1928}}\n**{{ltmcollection|25/995125.jpg|Underground station entrance, 1939}}\n**{{ltmcollection|51/9866051.jpg|Main line and Underground station entrances, 1974}}\n*[https://www.networkrail.co.uk/stations/cannon-street/ Station information] on Cannon Street railway station from [[Network Rail]]\n{{Circle line navbox}}\n{{District line navbox}}\n{{Transport in London}}\n{{Major railway stations in Britain}}\n{{TSGN and SE Stations|Hayes=y|Bexleyheath=y|Elmstead=y|Staplehurst=y|Hastings=y|Abbey Wood=y|Sidcup=y|Chatham=y|FCC None=y|SN None=y}}\n{{Jubilee line navbox}}\n{{Closed London Underground stations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cannon Street Station}}\n[[Category:Circle line stations]]\n[[Category:District line stations]]\n[[Category:Railway termini in London]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Tube stations in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Former South Eastern Railway (UK) stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1866]]\n[[Category:Former Metropolitan and Metropolitan District Joint Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1884]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Southeastern]]\n[[Category:Network Rail managed stations]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:John Hawkshaw railway stations]]\n[[Category:John Wolfe Barry railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations located underground in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:London station group]]\n[[Category:John Poulson buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other stations with the same name}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{short description|London railway and Underground station}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Cannon Street\n| alt_name      = London Cannon Street\n| manager       = [[Network Rail]]\n| owner         =\n| locale        = [[Cannon Street]]\n| borough       = [[City of London]]\n| platforms     = 7\n| fare_zone     = 1\n| railcode      = CST\n| railcode2     =\n| dft_category  = A\n| image_name    = Cannon Street station new building.JPG\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Main entrance\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.5104|-0.0907|type:railwaystation_region:GB-LND|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type      = Central London\n| years1        = 1 September 1866\n| years2        = 5 June 1926\n| years3        = 28 June 1926\n| years4        = 5 August 1974\n| years5        = 9 September 1974\n| events1       = Opened\n| events2       = Closed\n| events3       = Reopened\n| events4       = Closed\n| events5       = Reopened\n<!--| railexits0203 =\n| railexits0304 =\n| railexits0405 = {{increase}} 17.460\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 17.614\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 21.106\n| railexits0708 = {{increase}} 22.177\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 21.646\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 20.229\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 20.528\n| railexits1112 = {{decrease}} 20.223\n| railexits1213 = {{decrease}} 20.020\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 20.689 -->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 22.130\n| railexits1516 = {{decrease}} 21.242{{efn|This decrease was caused by a change in methodology which reduced usage figures at Cannon Street by 1.913 million. Without the changes, the usage would have been 23.155 million.}}\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 22.660\n| railexits1718 = {{increase}} 23.447\n| railexits1819 = {{decrease}} 20.615\n<!-- Interchange numbers should not be displayed as per consensus in the talk page discussion (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template_talk:Infobox_GB_station#Interchange_statistics,_2018); the number falls well below 10% of total entries/exits.\n| railint0203   =\n| railint0304   =\n| railint0405   =\n| railint0506   =\n| railint0607   =\n| railint0708   =\n| railint0809   =\n| railint0910   =\n| railint1011   =\n| railint1112   = {{pad|2em}}0.440\n| railint1213   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.437\n| railint1314   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 0.465\n| raillowint1415 = {{pad|2em}} ''not available''  the published figure of 2,350,974 seems unlikely\n| railint1516   = {{pad|2em}} 0.767\n| railint1617   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.714\n| railint1718   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 0.290 -->\n| interchange   = [[Bank\u2013Monument station|Bank]] {{rail-interchange|london|underground}} {{rail-interchange|london|dlr}}\n| interchange_note =<ref>{{Citation London station interchange February 2019}}</ref>\n| imagesize        = x240px\n| symbol           = rail\n| gridref          = TQ326808\n| original         = [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]]\n| pregroup         = [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]]\n| postgroup        = [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]]\n| access           = yes\n}}\n'''Cannon Street station''', also known as '''London Cannon Street''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CST/details.html |title=Station facilities for London Cannon Street |work=National Rail Enquiries |accessdate=29 May 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612010452/http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CST/details.html |archivedate=12 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a [[London station group|central London railway terminus]] and connected [[London Underground]] station in [[List of stations in London fare zone 1|Travelcard zone 1]] located on [[Cannon Street]] in the [[City of London]] and managed by [[Network Rail]]. It is one of two London termini of the [[South Eastern main line]], the other being {{rws|Charing Cross}}, while the Underground station is on the [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] and [[District line]]s, between [[Bank and Monument stations|Monument]] and [[Mansion House tube station|Mansion House]]. The station runs services by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]], mostly catering for commuters in southeast London and Kent, with occasional services further into the latter.\n\nThe station was built on a site of the medieval [[steelyard]], the trading base in England of the [[Hanseatic League]]. It was built by the [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]] in order to have a railway terminal in the City and compete with the rival [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]]. This required a new bridge across the [[River Thames]], which was constructed between 1863 and 1866. The station was initially a stop for continental services from Charing Cross, and that route was convenient for travel between the City and the [[West End of London|West End]], until the construction of the [[District Railway]]. It remained popular with commuters, though its off-peak services were discontinued in the early 20th century, leading to it being closed on Sundays for almost 100 years. The original hotel on the station was unsuccessful, and eventually closed. The station was controversially renovated in the late 1950s by [[John Poulson]], while further construction on top of the station building occurred during the City's 1980s property boom. The Poulson building was replaced in 2007 as part of a general renovation of the station to make it more accessible. As part of the [[Thameslink Programme]] development in the 2010s, it was re-opened on Sundays and began to offer more long-distance services in place of Charing Cross.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Cannon street railway bridge 2.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|Cannon Street Railway Bridge, 2005]]\nCannon Street is a terminal station, approached across the [[River Thames]] by the Cannon Street Railway Bridge. Its approach by rail is through a triangular connection to both {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} and {{stnlnk|Charing Cross}}. It is one of eighteen stations in the country that are managed by [[Network Rail]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our stations |url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/communities/passengers/our-stations/ |website=NetworkRail |accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere were originally eight platforms; a refurbishment in the late 1990s removed the original platform 1.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} It has entrances on [[Cannon Street]] itself and Dowgate Hill. It is located near the [[London Stone]] (to the north of the station).\n\n[[London Buses]] routes [[London Buses route 15|15]], [[London Buses route 17|17]], [[London Buses route 521|521]] and heritage route [[London Buses route 15 (Heritage)|15H]] and night routes [[London Buses route N15|N15]] and [[List of night buses in London#N199|N199]] serve the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.tfl.gov.uk/bus-route-maps/central-london-bus-map.pdf |title=Central London Bus Map |publisher=Transport for London |accessdate=17 July 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313082004/http://content.tfl.gov.uk/bus-route-maps/central-london-bus-map.pdf |archivedate=13 March 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Original structure===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station.jpg|thumb|left|Front of original station building, c. 1910]]\nCannon Street station was built on a site where the [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic]] merchants' steelyard had been based from the 10th century until 1598.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=127}} The site was proposed in 1860 by the [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]] (SER) in response to its rival, the [[London, Chatham & Dover Railway]] (LC&DR), extending a line into the [[City of London]] as far north as [[Ludgate Hill]]. The SER had already made plans to extend its line towards {{rws|Charing Cross}}, but decided that it should complement this with a terminus in the City.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=172}}\n\nIn 1861, the company obtained an act for a station in Cannon Street, a short distance from [[Mansion House, London|Mansion House]] and the [[Bank of England]].{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=172}} In addition to taking traffic from the LC&DR, the new station would provide a direct railway link between the City and the [[West End of London|West End]], over which a journey could be made in a fraction of the time taken travelling by road.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=114}} The approach was a {{convert|60|chain|adj=on}} branch of the line to Charing Cross, west of London Bridge. Work started on the station and its approach in July 1863.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}}\n\nThe station was opened on 1 September 1866{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}} at a cost of \u00a34 million (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|4|1866}} million).{{sfn|Ball|Sunderland|2002|p=214}} The original building was designed by [[John Hawkshaw|Sir John Hawkshaw]] and [[John Wolfe-Barry]] and was characterised by its two [[Christopher Wren]]-style towers, {{convert|23|ft|m|abbr=on}} square and {{convert|135|ft|m|abbr=on}} high, which faced on to the [[River Thames]]. The towers supported an iron train shed, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and crowned by a high single arch, almost semicircular, of glass and iron. The station is carried over [[Thames Street, London|Upper Thames Street]] on a brick viaduct, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and containing 27 million bricks.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2009|p=69}} Below this viaduct exist the remains of a number of Roman buildings, which form a [[scheduled ancient monument]].{{sfn|Allinson|Thornton|2014|p=58}} The bridge was open to pedestrians between 1872 and 1877; they paid a toll of [[Halfpenny (British pre-decimal coin)|\u00bdd]].{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=173}}\n\n[[File:Cannon Street Station 2.jpg|thumb|left|Original station viewed from the railway bridge, c. 1910]]\nThe five-storey City Terminus Hotel, which fronted the station, was opened in May 1867. It was an [[Italianate]] style hotel and forecourt, designed by [[Edward Middleton Barry|E. M. Barry]], and it provided many of the station's passenger facilities, as well as an appropriate architectural frontispiece to the street. This arrangement was very similar to that put in place at Charing Cross.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} The hotel was not profitable, and was over \u00a347,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|47000|1870|fmt=c|r=-3}}) in debt by 1870.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=120}} The City Terminus Hotel was renamed the Cannon Street Hotel in 1879.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} In July 1920, the hotel was the first meeting point of the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]]. Most of the hotel was closed in 1931, but the public rooms were kept open for meetings. The rest were converted into offices and renamed Southern House.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} The hotel is referred to in The Fire Sermon section of [[T. S. Eliot]]'s ''[[The Waste Land]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/47311/the-waste-land |title=The Waste Land by T. S. Eliot |first=Poetry |last=Foundation |date=15 May 2019 |website=Poetry Foundation}}</ref>\n\nUpon its opening Cannon Street station was a stopping point for all services to and from Charing Cross, including boat trains to Continental Europe. A shuttle service between the two stations ran every 20 minutes and became a popular way of travelling between the City and the West End.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=175}} However, the opening of the [[District Railway]] as far as [[Blackfriars tube station|Blackfriars]] caused traffic to decline, and its extension to [[Mansion House tube station|Mansion House]] the following year reduced it further. The SER's route could not compete with the Underground, which was more direct and reliable,{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=176}} but suburban traffic to Cannon Street remained popular, and the bridge was widened to {{convert|120|ft}} in the late 1880s, allowing ten tracks with sidings. The rebuilt bridge was opened on 13 February 1892.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=177}} The signal boxes outside the station were upgraded the following year.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=124}}\n\nThe [[London and Southwestern Railway]] (LSWR) became interested in using Cannon Street as a terminus, as it would allow a connection between [[London Waterloo railway station|Waterloo]] and the City.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=119}}\n\n===War years===\nWork on strengthening the bridge, by the addition of six new {{convert|443|ft|adj=on}} girders in between the existing ones, was completed in 1913.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|p=177}}\n\nMost Cannon Street train services ceased during [[World War I]]. Continental boat trains were stopped on 15 November 1914 and rerouted to Victoria. The station stopped being served by through services from Charing Cross on 31 December 1916, and was closed on Sundays. Services were reduced further on 1 May 1918, when it was closed after 3&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays and between 11&nbsp;a.m. and 4&nbsp;p.m. Mondays to Fridays. This allowed Cannon Street to be used as a goods depot for war supplies.{{sfn|Jackson|1984|pp=177\u2013178}}\n\nBetween 5 and 28 June 1926, the station was closed to allow the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]] to carry out various works, including the rebuilding of the platforms, relaying of the tracks and installation of a new system of electrical signalling \u2013 the four-aspect colour light scheme. The station was also renovated and the glass roof cleaned. The number of platforms was reduced from nine to eight, with five set aside for the new electric trains. The signal box spanning the width of the railway bridge was removed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannon Street Station Reopened |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=29 June 1926 |p=8 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS135469789&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In July 1939, Cannon Street was closed for a week following a fire in [[Borough Market]] which prevented any trains accessing it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannon Street Station Reopened |newspaper=The Times |date=25 July 1939 |p=9 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS153040121&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe station, which had been subject to structural neglect prior to [[World War II]], suffered extensive bomb damage and was hit by several incendiary devices which damaged the roof. A high explosive also hit platform 8.<ref>{{cite news |title=London Termini Bomb Damage |newspaper=The Times |date=19 November 1943 |p=8 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS136265075&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The original glass roof had been removed before the war, in an attempt to save it; however, the factory in which the roof was stored was itself badly bombed, destroying the roof.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}}\n\n===Redevelopment===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station (8417710796).jpg|thumb|upright|Cannon Street station in 1969, showing the easterly of the twin towers]]\nFollowing [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1948\u20131994#The 1940s: Nationalisation|nationalisation of the railways]] in 1948, the station was managed by the [[Southern Region of British Railways]]. The station's prime location coupled with the property boom of the 1950s and the need for [[British Rail]] to seek alternative revenue streams made war-damaged Cannon Street a key target for property developers.<ref name=times55/> Steam trains stopped running from Cannon Street in 1959.{{sfn|Davies|Grant|1983|p=47}}\n\nVarious plans were mooted for the reconstruction of the station, from the installation of a new ticket hall and concourse under Southern House in 1955 as part of British Rail's [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1948\u20131994#The Modernisation Plan|Modernisation Plan]] to the construction of a car park estimated to cost \u00a3125,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|125000|1955|fmt=c|r=-3}})<ref name=times55>{{cite news |title=Rebuilding of Cannon Street Station |newspaper=The Times |date=17 November 1955 |p=15 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS252269937&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and even a helipad.{{efn|The preferred site was the old [[Nine Elms]] goods yard in [[Battersea]]}}<ref>{{cite news |title=First Choice for Helicopter Site |work=The Times |date=3 March 1962 |p=6 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS102851171&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1962, the [[British Transport Commission]] entered into an agreement with Town & Country Properties for the construction of a multi-storey office building above the station with {{convert|154000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of floor space. The cost of the development was \u00a32.35&nbsp;million (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|2.35|1965}} million) and it was scheduled for completion by June 1965.<ref>{{cite news |title=Big New Buildings Over Two London Termini |newspaper=The Times |date=22 March 1962 |p=12 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS203645558&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for redevelopment, the remains of the train shed roof had been demolished in 1958, and Barry's hotel (which had been used as offices since 1931) soon followed in 1960.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=128}} The architect selected to design the new building was [[John Poulson]] who was good friends with Graham Tunbridge, a British Rail surveyor whom he had met during the war. Poulson took advantage of this friendship to win contracts for the redevelopment of various British Rail termini. He paid Tunbridge a weekly income of \u00a325 and received in return building contracts, including the rebuilding of [[London Waterloo station|Waterloo]] and [[East Croydon station]]s. At his trial in 1974, Poulson admitted that, shortly before receiving the Cannon Street building contract, he had given Tunbridge a cheque for \u00a3200 and a suit worth \u00a380.<ref>{{cite news |title=John Poulson tells of gifts to rail man |newspaper=The Times |date=15 January 1974|p=4|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS68254255&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Poulson was later found guilty of corruption charges and given a seven-year concurrent sentence; Tunbridge received a 15-month suspended sentence and a \u00a34,000 fine for his role in the affair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seven-year concurrent sentence on Mr Poulson|newspaper=The Times|date=16 March 1974 |p=3|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS50559600&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAll that now remains of the original station architecture are the twin {{convert|120|ft|m|abbr=on}} yellow brick towers at the country-end and parts of the low flanking walls.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}}\n\n===Modern era===\n[[File:Cannon Street Station 3.jpg|thumb|right|[[John Poulson]]'s office block in 2007 prior to redevelopment]]\nThe station's twin brick towers were [[listed building|listed Grade II]] in 1972.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1192326 |desc=Pair of Towers at Cannon Street Station: Western Tower to Cannon Street Station |grade=II |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1359145 |desc=Eastern Tower to Cannon Street Station: Pair of Towers at Cannon Street Station |grade=II |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1974, the station was closed for five weeks from 2 August to 9 September to enable alterations to be made to the track and the approaches to London Bridge to be resignalled. Traffic was diverted to London Bridge, Charing Cross and {{LUL stations|station=Blackfriars}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street station closing for five weeks|newspaper=The Times|date=29 July 1974|p=3|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS51477245&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 March 1976, a [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) bomb of about 10&nbsp;lb (4.5&nbsp;kg) exploded on an empty commuter train leaving Cannon Street, injuring eight people on another train travelling alongside.{{efn|Had the bomb exploded 13 minutes earlier it would have caused widespread carnage as the train had been carrying hundreds of commuters on a service from [[Sevenoaks railway station|Sevenoaks]].<ref name=sevenoaks/>}}<ref name=sevenoaks>{{cite news|title=Thirteen minutes saved hundreds on the 7.49 from Sevenoaks|work=The Times|date=5 March 1976|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS33783397&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 1984, it was reported in ''[[The Times]]'' that Cannon Street was to close. At the time, the station had been closed for weekends and evenings, and the publication of British Rail's new timetable for 1984\u20131985 revealed that it would lose all its direct off-peak services to the south-east. Services from Sevenoaks, {{stnlnk|Orpington}}, {{stnlnk|Hayes}}, {{stnlnk|Dartford}}, {{stnlnk|Sidcup}}, {{stnlnk|Bexleyheath}}, {{stnlnk|Woolwich}}, [[Lewisham station|Lewisham]] and [[Greenwich station|Greenwich]] would instead terminate at {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} except during peak hours.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street rail station 'near to closure'|newspaper=The Times|date=15 February 1984|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS34180687&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> This was denied by British Rail (Southern)'s manager David Kirby, who pointed out that it had invested \u00a310&nbsp;million in redecking the railway bridge, and that passengers travelling from the south-east during off-peak hours would most likely be visiting the [[West End of London|West End]] and not [[City of London|the City]].<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Kirby|title=Cannon Street Station|newspaper=The Times|date=22 February 1984|p=15|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=&docId=CS252939862&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, the twin towers were restored in a project costing \u00a3242,000 (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|242000|1972|fmt=c|r=-3}}). The works revealed that the east tower still contained a large water tank which was used during the days of steam traction to replenish locomotives and to power the station's hydraulic systems. The brickwork was repaired, cleaned and repointed, and the [[weather vane]]s gilded to complement the dome of nearby [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. This work was one of the Railway Heritage Trust's first projects and coincided with an exhibition held in the station in August of the same year to mark its 150th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Restoration at Cannon Street|newspaper=The Times|date=2 December 1985|p=2|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS34312578&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plumber's Apprentice.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The ''Plumber's Apprentice'' by [[Martin Jennings]], unveiled in 2011 to mark the 400th anniversary of the [[Worshipful Company of Plumbers]] whose Guild Hall was demolished to make way for the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/plumber-s-apprentice-statue |title=Statue: Plumber's Apprentice statue |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=London Remembers |access-date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408005949/http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/plumber-s-apprentice-statue |archivedate=8 April 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nIn the 1980s, there was another property boom and British Rail again began looking into further commercial uses of the Cannon Street landspace, including {{convert|500000|sqft}} of office space.<ref>{{cite news|first=Judith|last=Hutley|title=BR names Cannon St shortlist|newspaper=The Times|date=17 March 1986|p=20|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF500456800&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[air rights]] over the platforms to the rear of Poulson's office were sold to Speyhawk which appointed [[Bovis Construction]] to build a free-standing structure comprising two office blocks on a 6,000 tonne steel deck constructed over the station's eight platforms.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=123}} The Cannons Club, a sports club, was founded beneath the station's arches around this time, and quickly became one of the most prestigious [[squash (sport)|squash]] clubs in the country. [[InterCity]], the high-speed arm of British Rail, subsequently sponsored the National Squash Championships and National Squash Challenge.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colin|last=McQuillan|title=Branching out with more support|newspaper=The Times|date=17 September 1986|p=37|accessdate=18 July 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF501698917&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe larger office block, the \"Atrium building\", provides {{convert|190000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space on six floors and is linked to the smaller building, the \"River building\", via a glazed link raised through a central glazed atrium. The River building, which has two storeys, is built on the steel deck and contained within the station's two flank walls, which were rebuilt, providing {{convert|95000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space. This building projects slightly beyond the restored twin towers which form the riverside boundary to the development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Construction Contracts: Building Over Busy Station|work=Financial Times|date=6 March 1989}}</ref> The Atrium building was later let to the [[London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange|London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange (Liffe)]]. The River building has a {{convert|1|acre|ha}} roof garden. The project cost around \u00a3500,000 and was laid to comply with planning restrictions which required the building to be low and flat to maintain the sight lines from St Paul's to [[Tower Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=City garden feels the frost|work=The Times|date=27 November 1991|p=40|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF501903210&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nPlanning permission was granted in March 2007 to replace the Poulson building, with a new air rights building designed by Foggo Associates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/dailynews/foggo_wins_green_light_for_cannon_street_station_redesign.html|title=Foggo Wins Green Light for Cannon Street Station Redesign|publisher=Architects Journal|date=21 March 2007}}</ref> [[Gerald D. Hines|Hines]], the US developer, led a \u00a3360&nbsp;million project involving the demolition of Poulson's office block, replacing it with a mixed-use development containing more than {{convert|400000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of office space alongside {{convert|17000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of station retail space.{{sfn|Allinson|Thornton|2014|p=58}} The redevelopment was part of a larger regeneration programme undertaken by [[Network Rail]] to modernise and \"unlock the commercial potential\" of the main London termini; {{stnlnk|Euston}} and {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} were also redeveloped. Network Rail's director of commercial property said that the finished station would be \"less congested and more accessible for passengers.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannon Street to lead revamp of stations|newspaper=The Times|date=6 April 2007|p=55|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF503522467&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Cannon Street won the award for \"Major Station of the Year\" at the 2013 National Rail Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Boom time for Cannon Street station |first=Paul |last=Prentice |magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]] |date=27 November 2013 |issue=736 |pages=48\u201353 |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the station's opening hours were extended to 0500\u20130100 Monday to Sunday (prior to this, the station had been closed on Sundays and during the evenings), and several services which previously terminated at Charing Cross were diverted to Cannon Street as a result of [[Thameslink Programme]] works. Some of these services will revert to terminating at Charing Cross following the completion of the works, while services from the [[Greenwich line]] and from [[New Cross railway station|New Cross]] and [[St Johns railway station|St Johns]] will permanently run to Cannon Street due to the removal of the Spa Road Junction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southernrailway.com/download/32760/january-impacts/|title=Impacts and Travel Advice|publisher=Southern Railway|date=January 2015|accessdate=18 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420133712/http://www.southernrailway.com/download/32760/january-impacts/|archivedate=20 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/news/four-weeks-to-go-before-cross-london-thameslink-trains-stop-calling-at-london-bridge-rail-station|title=Four Weeks To Go Before Cross-London Thameslink Trains Stop Calling At London Bridge|work=Network Rail News|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==National Rail==\n[[File:Cannon Street 2020.jpg|thumb|right|The station viewed from the south bank of the Thames, 2020]]\nThe station connects the south side of the City to south and south-east London via {{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}} station. Some services run directly into Cannon Street from [[Kent]] and [[East Sussex]], but only during rush hours. Occasionally during the weekends when track maintenance is in progress, the station serves as an intermediate station between London Bridge and {{stnlnk|Charing Cross}}. Either trains reverse at the station or rail passengers change trains here. From 1918 to 2015, the station was closed on Sundays; this changed with Southeastern's introduction of a new timetable from January 2015 which resulted in the station's opening hours being extended over the entire week,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teamlondonbridge.co.uk/newsdetails.aspx?ref=2889 |title=Southeastern consults on changes to timetable in December 2014 |work=Team London Bridge |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003061510/http://www.teamlondonbridge.co.uk/newsdetails.aspx?ref=2889 |archivedate=3 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> except when engineering works require its closure and services are diverted to Charing Cross.<ref>{{cite news |last=Collier |first=Hatty |url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/12898684.London_Bridge_and_Cannon_Street_closed_to_Southeastern_passengers_on_Sunday/ |title=London Bridge and Cannon Street closed to Southeastern passengers on Sunday |work=[[News Shopper]] |date=18 April 2015 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150809032049/http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/12898684.London_Bridge_and_Cannon_Street_closed_to_Southeastern_passengers_on_Sunday/ |archivedate=9 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Services===\nThe typical off-peak service from the station is:<ref name=tt>{{cite web|url=https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/travel-information/more-travel-help/station-information/stations/london-cannon-street|title=Timetables for London Cannon Street|publisher=Southeastern|id=Select an individual timetable to verify the service information|accessdate=19 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719120708/https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/travel-information/more-travel-help/station-information/stations/london-cannon-street|archivedate=19 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n* 2&nbsp;trains per hour (tph) \u2013 {{Stnlnk|Hayes}} via [[Lewisham station|Lewisham]]\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 {{Stnlnk|Orpington}} via {{Stnlnk|Grove Park}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Greenwich and [[Woolwich Arsenal station|Woolwich Arsenal]] to {{stnlnk|Slade Green}} then return via {{Stnlnk|Sidcup}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Greenwich and Woolwich Arsenal to Slade Green then return via {{Stnlnk|Barnehurst}} and {{Stnlnk|Bexleyheath}}\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Bexleyheath to Barnehurst, then return via Woolwich Arsenal and Greenwich\n* 2&nbsp;tph \u2013 Loop service via Sidcup to {{Stnlnk|Crayford}}, then return via [[Woolwich Arsenal station|Woolwich Arsenal]] and {{stnlnk|Greenwich}}\n\nDuring peak hours, there are also services to Hastings, Tunbridge Wells, Ore and to Ramsgate or Broadstairs via Chatham.<ref name=tt/>\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|previous={{LUL stations|station=London Bridge}}|route=[[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]<br><small>[[South Eastern main line]]|next=|col={{SE color}}}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n===Accidents and incidents===\n*On 26 December 1867, seven passengers and three train crew members were injured when, \"during a very thick fog\", a train arriving at Cannon Street from [[Greenwich station|Greenwich]] collided with another from [[London Waterloo station|Waterloo]] due to a signaller's error.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=2888|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 26th December 1867 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 27 June 1914, one person was killed and 20 were injured in a collision and subsequent derailment at Cannon Street. A train departing for {{rws|Hastings}} was in a side-long collision with a train arriving, across its path, from {{rws|Plumstead}} and, although the collision occurred at low speed, part of the Plumstead service was derailed and one of its carriages overturned. The driver of the Plumstead service was blamed for a failure to observe, and a misreading of, signals which took his train into the path of the Hastings-bound service. An investigation found the man who died was likely leaning out of the window at the moment his carriage overturned, and he might have avoided serious injury had he been seated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=407|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 27th June 1914 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 16 July 1919, 75 people were injured or left shaken when a train arriving from {{rws|Dartford}} hit the buffers at the end of Cannon Street's platform seven. Twelve of the injured required hospital treatment. A [[Board of Trade]] report into the incident blamed \"an error of judgment\" on the driver's part while he was braking on his approach to the platform end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/docsummary.php?docID=2278|title=Accident Returns: Extract for the Accident at Cannon Street on 16th July 1919 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 11 May 1941, the station was bombed in a [[Luftwaffe]] air raid. At least one locomotive was severely damaged.<ref name=Earnshaw8>{{cite book |last=Earnshaw |first=Alan |title=Trains in Trouble: Vol. 8 |year=1993 |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=Penryn |isbn=0-906899-52-4 |page=20 }}</ref>\n*On 20 March 1951, a [[diesel electric multiple unit]] and an [[electric multiple unit]] were in a side-long collision when the driver of the latter misread signals.<ref name=Earnshaw5>{{cite book |last=Earnshaw |first=Alan |title=Trains in Trouble: Vol. 5 |year=1989 |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=Penryn |isbn=0-906899-35-4 |pages=40\u201341 }}</ref>\n*On 5 April 1957, the signal box was destroyed by a fire due to an electrical fault. The station was consequently put out of action. Using hand signals, a skeleton service was put in place on 8 April. A temporary signal box was erected which came into operation on 5 May. Steam locomotives were temporarily banned from using the station, with [[British Rail Class 201|Hastings Units]] being introduced into service earlier than planned. A full service was resumed from 6 May. Construction of a new signal box began on 19 April and it came into service on 16 December.<ref name=Glover>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric |first=John |last=Glover |publisher=Ian Allan |location=Hersham |year=2001 |pages=138\u201339 |isbn=0-7110-2807-9}}</ref>\n*On 20 March 1961, a side-long collision and partial derailment resulted in injury to 12 people aboard an arriving service whose driver inadvertently passed a red signal and ran into an empty train as it left Cannon Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=410|title=Accident at Cannon Street on 20th March 1961 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n*On 4 March 1976, [[Cannon Street train bombing|a bomb exploded]] on an empty electric multiple unit at the station. Eight people in an adjacent train were injured.<ref name=Moody>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric 1909\u20131979 |first=G. T. |last=Moody |origyear=1957 |year=1979 |edition=Fifth |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd |location=Shepperton |page=231 |isbn=0-7110-0924-4}}</ref>\n* On 20 August 1989, the [[Marchioness disaster|''Marchioness'' pleasure boat sank]] close to Cannon Street Railway Bridge, killing 51 people.{{sfn|Christopher|2015|p=124}}\n*On 8 January 1991, [[Cannon Street station rail crash|two people were killed and hundreds were injured]] when an electric multiple unit failed to stop on a dead-end platform and collided with the buffers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|title=On this Day : 8 January 1991: One dead as train crashes into buffers|work=BBC News|accessdate=17 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108160834/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|archivedate=8 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==London Underground==\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Cannon Street|symbol=underground\n| alt_name      =\n| manager       = [[London Underground]]\n| manager1      =\n| manager2      =\n| owner         =\n| owner1        =\n| owner2        =\n| locale        = [[Cannon Street]]\n| borough       = [[City of London]]\n| platforms     = 2\n| fare_zone     = 1\n| fare_zone_1   =\n| image_name    = Cannon Street tube stn entrance 2012.JPG\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Entrance from Dowgate Hill\n| coordinates   = \n| map_type      =\n| years1        = 1884\n| years2        = \n| years3        =\n| events1       = Opened (MICCR)\n| events2       =\n| events3       =\n<!--| tubeexits03   =\n| tubeexits04   = {{increase}} 4.096\n| tubeexits05   =\n| tubeexits06   = 4.325\n| tubeexits07   = {{decrease}} 4.11\n| tubeexits08   = {{increase}} 4.54\n| tubeexits09   = {{decrease}} 3.933-->\n| access = yes\n| access_note = (Westbound only)<ref>{{citation step free tube map}}</ref>\n}}\nThe London Underground station is sub-surface, situated immediately below the main line station. It is served by the [[District line|District]] and [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle line]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|title=Standard Tube Map|publisher=Transport for London|accessdate=19 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625083557/http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Entrances are located on Cannon Street, Dowgate Hill, and on the main line concourse upstairs at the National Rail station, providing an interconnection for commuters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@51.5115103,-0.0908027,3a,75y,79.66h,83.74t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sEFgTBF1MFT_tj2iqWBZ-ww!2e0!7i13312!8i6656|title=Cannon Street Underground Station|publisher=Google Maps|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> An [[out of station interchange]] with [[Bank and Monument stations|Bank station]] has been running since 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citymetric.com/transport/london-s-tube-map-needs-rethink-how-it-shows-bankmonument-interchange-4425|title=London's Tube Map needs to rethink how it shows Bank / Monument interchange|work=City Metric|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===History===\nBy 1876, the [[Metropolitan Railway]] (MR) and [[District Railway]] (DR) had constructed the majority of the Inner Circle (now the Circle line), reaching {{LUL stations|station=Aldgate}} and {{LUL stations|station=Mansion House}} respectively.{{sfn|Day|Reed|2008|pp=255\u2013256}} The companies were in dispute over the completion of the route as the DR was struggling financially and the MR was concerned that completion would affect its revenues through increased competition from the DR in the City area. In 1874, city financiers who were keen to see the line completed established the Metropolitan Inner Circle Completion Railway (MICCR) to link Mansion House to Aldgate.{{sfn|Brandon|2013|p=58}}{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=64}} Forced into action, the MR bought out the company, and it and the DR began construction of the final section of the Inner Circle in 1879.{{sfn|Brandon|2013|p=58}}\n\nOn 6 October 1884, the final section of the Inner Circle was opened, along with Cannon Street station.{{sfn|Lee|1956|p=47}} Initially, the station was served by trains of both companies as part of the circular Inner Circle service, but various operational patterns have been used during the station's life.{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=65}} The Inner Circle service achieved a separate identity as the Circle line in 1949, although its trains were still provided by the District or Metropolitan lines.{{sfn|Martin|2012|p=66}}\n\nA station here was part of the abandoned phase two expansion of the Fleet line (now [[Jubilee line]]). It had originally been planned in 1943, and was revived as a major transport plan in 1965.{{sfn|Mitchell|2003|p=1}} London Transport spent \u00a310m (now \u00a3{{inflation|UK|10|1972}}m) in 1972 safeguarding the route underneath Cannon Street and building reinforcements for laying a tube in the water-bearing ground around the station. The plan was abandoned in the early 1980s in favour of the current extension further south.{{sfn|Mitchell|2003|p=3-4}}\n\nThe Underground station underwent major reconstruction at the same time as the main line station, with the work being completed in 2012. From 14 December 2014, the station's opening hours changed significantly, with the station opening on Sundays and no longer closing early in the evenings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenorthbank.org/northbank-news/increased-service-of-district-line-trains-from-14th-dec/|title=Increased Services of District Line Trains from 14 Dec|work=Northbank News|accessdate=19 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404130041/https://www.thenorthbank.org/northbank-news/increased-service-of-district-line-trains-from-14th-dec/|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station previously had restricted opening hours because it primarily served the local financial services sector, so there was low demand for services outside office hours. However, with the main line station's opening hours being extended due to the [[Thameslink Programme]], the Underground station's opening hours were changed to accommodate the additional passengers.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{s-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Circle|previous=Mansion House|next=Monument|type=Victoria|type2=Tower Hill}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=District|previous=Mansion House|next=Monument|type=Three}}\n{{s-note|text=Abandoned plans}}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Jubilee|previous=Ludgate Circus|next=Fenchurch Street|type2=Phases2&3|notemid=Phase 2 (never constructed)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin|25em}}\n* {{cite book |last=Allinson|first=Ken|last2=Thornton|first2=Victoria|title=London's Contemporary Architecture: An Explorer's Guide|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=978-1-317-69046-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ball|first=Michael|last2=Sunderland|first2=David|title=An Economic History of London 1800\u20131914|year=2002|isbn=978-1-134-54030-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Brandon|first=David|title=London And The Victorian Railway|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2013|isbn=978-1-445-62926-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Christopher|first=John|title=London's Historic Railway Stations Through Time|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2015|isbn=978-1-445-65111-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Day |first1=John R. |last2=Reed |first2=John |title=The Story of London's Underground |edition=10th |year=2008 |origyear=1963 |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=978-1-85414-316-7 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Davies|first1=R.|last2=Grant|first2=M.D.|title=London and its Railways|publisher=David & Charles|year=1983|isbn=0-7153-8107-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gray|first=Adrian|title=South Eastern Railway|publisher=Middleton Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0-906520-85-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jackson|first=Alan| year = 1984 |origyear=1969 | title = London's Termini | publisher = David & Charles | edition=New Revised| isbn = 0-330-02747-6|location=London|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lee|first=Charles Edward|title=The Metropolitan District Railway|publisher=Oakwood Press|year=1956|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Martin|first=Andrew|title=Underground, Overground: A Passenger's History of the Tube|publisher=Profile Books|year=2012|isbn=978-1-847-65807-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=McCarthy |first1=Colin |last2=McCarthy |first2=David |title = Railways of Britain \u2013 London North of the Thames |publisher = Ian Allan Publishing |location= Hersham, Surrey |isbn=978-0-7110-3346-7 |year=2009 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Mitchell|first=Bob|title=Jubilee Line Extension: From Concept to Completion|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=2003|isbn=978-0-727-73028-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Weinreb|first=Ben|last2=Hibbert|first2=Christopher|last3=Keay|first3=Julia|last4=Keay|first4=John|title=The London Encyclopedia|publisher=Pan MacMillan|year=2008|isbn=978-1-4050-4924-5|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cannon Street station}}\n* [https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/collections/collections-online/photographs/ London Transport Museum Photographic Archive]\n**{{ltmcollection|49/9889749.jpg|Underground station, 1896}}\n**{{ltmcollection|61/9889861.jpg|Underground station and Cannon Street Hotel, 1916}}\n**{{ltmcollection|70/9872970.jpg|Booking hall, 1928}}\n**{{ltmcollection|25/995125.jpg|Underground station entrance, 1939}}\n**{{ltmcollection|51/9866051.jpg|Main line and Underground station entrances, 1974}}\n*[https://www.networkrail.co.uk/stations/cannon-street/ Station information] on Cannon Street railway station from [[Network Rail]]\n{{Circle line navbox}}\n{{District line navbox}}\n{{Transport in London}}\n{{Major railway stations in Britain}}\n{{TSGN and SE Stations|Hayes=y|Bexleyheath=y|Elmstead=y|Staplehurst=y|Hastings=y|Abbey Wood=y|Sidcup=y|Chatham=y|FCC None=y|SN None=y}}\n{{Jubilee line navbox}}\n{{Closed London Underground stations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cannon Street Station}}\n[[Category:Circle line stations]]\n[[Category:District line stations]]\n[[Category:Railway termini in London]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Tube stations in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Former South Eastern Railway (UK) stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1866]]\n[[Category:Former Metropolitan and Metropolitan District Joint Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1884]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Southeastern]]\n[[Category:Network Rail managed stations]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:John Hawkshaw railway stations]]\n[[Category:John Wolfe Barry railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations located underground in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:London station group]]\n[[Category:John Poulson buildings]]\n", "name_user": "GrindtXX", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLocation:def article not necessary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannon_Street_station"}
{"title_page": "Essen", "text_new": "{{About}}\n{{Infobox German location\n|type          = city\n|image_photo = {{Photomontage|position=center\n|photo1a = Villa huegel.jpg\n|photo2a = ThyssenKrupp Quartier (31798903101).jpg\n|photo2b = Essen-S\u00fcdviertel Luft.jpg\n|photo3a = Grillo-Theater-2012.jpg\n|photo3b = Schloss-Borbeck-Komplettansicht-Sonnenuntergang-2012.jpg\n|photo4a =Zollverein Schacht 12.jpg\n|photo4b = Essen Einkaufsstadt Hotel Handelshof 2014.jpg\n|photo5a = Aalto-Theater-Abends-02-2014.jpg\n|size = 280\n|spacing = 2\n|color = #FFFFFF\n|border = 0}}\n|image_caption = Clockwise from top: [[Villa H\u00fcgel]], Essen Business District, Schlo\u00df Borbeck, Hotel Handelshof, [[Aalto Theatre]], UNESCO world heritage site [[Zeche Zollverein]], [[Grillo-Theater]], and [[ThyssenKrupp]] Headquarters.\n|image_flag    = Flagge Essen.svg\n|image_coa     = DEU Essen COA.svg\n|coordinates   = {{coord|51|27|3|N|7|0|47|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan    = North rhine w E.svg\n|state         = North Rhine-Westphalia\n|region        = [[D\u00fcsseldorf (region)|D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n|district      = urban\n|elevation     = 116\n|area          = 210.32\n<!-- |population= |pop_ref= |population_as_of= All filled in by [[Template:Infobox German location]] via [[Template:Metadata Population DE-NW]] -->\n|postal_code   = 45001\u201345359\n|PLZ-alt       = 4300\n|area_code     = 0201, 02054 ([[Kettwig]])\n|licence       = E\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 05 1 13 000\n|NUTS = DEA13\n|LOCODE = DE ESS\n|divisions = 9 districts, 50 boroughs\n|website = [https://www.essen.de/ www.essen.de]<br />[https://www.visitessen.de/ www.visitessen.de]\n|mayor = [[Thomas Kufen]]\n|B\u00fcrgermeistertitel = Oberb\u00fcrgermeister\n|party = CDU\n}}\n'''Essen''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u025bsn\u0329|-|De-Essen.ogg}}; [[Latin]]: ''Assindia'') is the central and second largest city of the [[Ruhr]], the largest urban area in [[Germany]]. Its population of 583,393 makes it the [[List of cities in Germany by population|ninth largest city of Germany]], as well as the fourth largest city of the federal state of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. On the [[Ruhr (river)|Ruhr]] and [[Emscher]] rivers, Essen geographically is part of the [[Rhineland]] and the larger [[Rhine-Ruhr|Rhine-Ruhr Metropolitan Region]]. The [[Ruhrdeutsch]] [[regiolect]] spoken in the region has strong influences of both [[Low German]] ([[Westphalian language|Westphalian]]) and [[Low Franconian]] ([[East Bergish]]).\n\nEssen is seat to several of the region's authorities, as well as to eight of the 100 largest publicly held German corporations regarding turnover, including two [[DAX]] corporations. Essen is often considered the energy capital of Germany with [[E.ON]] and [[RWE]], Germany's largest energy providers, both headquartered in the city. Essen is also known for its impact on the arts through the respected [[Folkwang University of the Arts]], its Zollverein School of Management and Design, and the [[Red Dot]] industrial product design award. In early 2003, the universities of Essen and the nearby city of [[Duisburg]] (both established in 1972) were merged into the [[University of Duisburg-Essen]] with campuses in both cities and a [[university hospital]] in Essen. In 1958, Essen was chosen to serve as the seat to a [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Essen|Roman Catholic diocese]] (often referred to as ''Ruhrbistum'' or ''diocese of the Ruhr'').\n\nFounded around 845, Essen remained a small town within the sphere of influence of an important [[Imperial Abbey|ecclesiastical principality]] ([[Essen Abbey]]) until the onset of industrialization. The city then \u2014 especially through the [[Krupp]] family iron works \u2014 became one of Germany's most important coal and steel centers. Essen, until the 1970s, attracted workers from all over the country; it was the 5th-largest city in Germany between 1929 and 1988, peaking at over 730,000 inhabitants in 1962. Following the region-wide decline of heavy industries in the last decades of the 20th century, the city has seen the development of a strong [[tertiary sector of the economy]]. The most notable witness of this ''Strukturwandel'' (structural change) is the [[Zollverein Coal Mine Industrial Complex]], which has once been the largest of its kind in Europe. Ultimately closed in 1993, both the [[coking plant]] and the [[coal mine|mine]] have been inscribed in the list of [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Sites]] since 2001.\n\nNotable accomplishments of the city in recent years include the title of [[European Capital of Culture]] on behalf of the whole Ruhr area in 2010 and the selection as the [[European Green Capital]] for 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/environment/europeangreencapital/applying-for-the-award/2017-egca-applicant-cities/|title=European Green Capital|website=ec.europa.eu|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== General ===\n<!-- Please do not change the alignment of the column content since they reflect the geographic positions. -->\n{| style=\"width: 400px; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right; width:25%; vertical-align:bottom;\"| [[File:DEU Oberhausen COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Oberhausen]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:10%; vertical-align:bottom;\"| [[File:DEU Bottrop COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Bottrop]]\n| style=\"text-align:left; width:15%; vertical-align:bottom;\"| [[File:DEU Gladbeck COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Gladbeck]]\n| style=\"text-align:left; width:25%; vertical-align:bottom;\"| [[File:DEU Gelsenkirchen COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Gelsenkirchen]]\n|-\n| style=\"width:25%; text-align:right;\"| [[File:DEU Muelheim an der Ruhr COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]]\n| style=\"width:50%; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| [[File:Essen Stadtteile und Stadtbezirke.svg|100px|center|Map of the Districts and Boroughs of Essen]] Essen<br /><small>(Map of districts and boroughs)</small>\n| style=\"width:25%; text-align:left;\"| [[File:Stadtwappen der kreisfreien Stadt Bochum.svg|20px]]<br />[[Bochum]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right; width:25%; vertical-align:top;\"| [[File:DEU Ratingen COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Ratingen]]\n| style=\"text-align:right; width:25%; vertical-align:top;\"| [[File:DEU Heiligenhaus COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Heiligenhaus]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:25%; vertical-align:top;\"| [[File:DEU Velbert COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Velbert]]\n| style=\"text-align:left; width:25%; vertical-align:top;\"| [[File:DEU Hattingen COA.svg|20px]]<br />[[Hattingen]]\n|-\n|}\nEssen is located in the centre of the [[Ruhr]] area, one of the largest [[urban area]]s in Europe (see also: [[megalopolis (city type)|megalopolis]]), comprising eleven [[independent city|independent cities]] and four [[district]]s with some 5.3 million inhabitants. The city limits of Essen itself are {{convert|87|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long and border ten cities, five independent and five ''kreisangeh\u00f6rig'' (i.e., belonging to a district), with a total population of approximately 1.4 million. The city extends over {{convert|21|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from north to south and {{convert|17|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from west to east, mainly north of the [[Ruhr (river)|River Ruhr]].\n\nThe Ruhr forms the ''Lake Baldeney'' [[reservoir]] in the boroughs of Fischlaken, Kupferdreh, Heisingen and [[Essen-Werden|Werden]]. The lake, a popular recreational area, dates from 1931 to 1933, when some thousands of unemployed [[coal miner]]s dredged it with primitive tools. Generally, large areas south of the River Ruhr (including the suburbs of Schuir and [[Kettwig]]) are quite green and are often quoted as examples of rural structures in the otherwise relatively densely populated central Ruhr area. According to the [[Federal Statistical Office of Germany]], Essen with 9.2% of its area covered by recreational green is the greenest city in [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-125300649.html|title=Kommunen: Der Tausendf\u00fc\u00dfler|date=October 2014|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> and the third-greenest city in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/panorama/reise-leben/top-ten-das-sind-deutschlands-gruenste-staedte/4369498.html|title=Top ten: Das sind Deutschlands gr\u00fcnste St\u00e4dte|website=www.handelsblatt.com|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> The city has been shortlisted for the title of [[European Green Capital]] two consecutive times, for 2016 and 2017, winning for 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/environment/europeangreencapital/media-corner/press-releases/index.html|title=European Green Capital|website=ec.europa.eu|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> The city was singled out for its exemplary practices in protecting and enhancing nature and biodiversity and efforts to reduce water consumption. Essen participates in a variety of networks and initiatives to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and to improve the city's resilience in the face of climate change.\n\nThe lowest point can be found in the northern borough of Karnap at {{convert|26.5|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}, the highest point in the borough of Heidhausen at {{convert|202.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}. The average elevation is {{convert|116|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n=== City districts ===\n[[File:Essen hbf 1817.jpg|thumb|Main station]]\nEssen comprises fifty boroughs which in turn are grouped into nine suburban districts (called ''[[Stadtbezirk]]e'') often named after the most important boroughs. Each Stadtbezirk is assigned a [[Roman numeral]] and has a local body of nineteen members with limited authority. Most of the boroughs were originally independent municipalities but were gradually annexed from 1901 to 1975. This long-lasting process of annexation has led to a strong identification of the population with \"their\" boroughs or districts and to a rare peculiarity: The borough of [[Kettwig]], located south of the Ruhr River, and which was not annexed until 1975, has its own [[Telephone numbering plan|area code]]. Additionally (allegedly due to relatively high church tax incomes), the Archbishop of Cologne managed to keep Kettwig directly subject to the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cologne|Archdiocese of Cologne]], whereas all other boroughs of Essen and some neighboring cities constitute the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Essen|Diocese of Essen]]''.''\n\n=== Climate ===\nEssen has a \"true\"''/''typical [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfb'') with relatively mild winters and cool summers (different of [[Berlin]] or [[Stuttgart]]). Without large mountains and the presence of inland seas, it ends up extending a predominantly [[Oceanic climate|marine climate]] is found in '''Essen''', usually a little more extreme and drier in other continents in such [[Location|geographical location]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=1401&cityname=Essen,+North+Rhine-Westphalia,+Germany&units=|title=Essen, Germany K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Its average annual temperature is {{convert|10|C|F|0}}: {{convert|13.3|C|F|0}} during the day and {{convert|6.7|C|F|0}} at night. The average annual precipitation is {{convert|934|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}. The coldest month of the year is January, when the average temperature is {{convert|2.4|C|F|0}}. The warmest months are July and August, with an average temperature of {{convert|18|C|F|0}}.<ref name = wmo/> The record high is {{Convert|36.6|C|F|0}} and the record low is {{Convert|-24|C|F|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meteorologyclimate.com/extreme-temperature-records.htm|title=Extreme temperature records since 1850|website=meteorologyclimate.com|accessdate=12 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329142642/http://www.meteorologyclimate.com/extreme-temperature-records.htm|archive-date=2017-03-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = 100%\n|lo